deck_excerpt: Super Quant Maliss  / Reutlingen WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Jens Kothe

Tournament: Reutlingen WCQ Regional – November 29th 2025

Placement: Top 8

Competetive rogue vendread deck with fiendsmith incorporated as a second engine. Summoner monk is used as a bridge to connect both engines together ; same goes as well for vendread charge to make Exciton! Deck is very combo Heavy with many lines. You can bridge to any ritual monster or spells in the game with the vendreads. So yes mitsurugui can be incorporated. So far the deck can still be improved to your liking. Honorable mention if you would want to use vendread Reunion to extend your combos you'll need 2 slayers an 1 Battlelord but if you want more protection add 2 Battlelords in main or side deck. Battlelord is an excellent side deck card. Hope you enjoy have fun! I almost forgot the deck can draw 5 with 1 necromancer all you need is number 60, crosssheep and sucker you can also with just 1 normal Summon of dark necromancer and any 1 ritual in hand make SP little knight with 2 banish, slayer with 2 banish, Battlelord with 2 banish on turn 1 with a total of 6 banishes plus if you have Engraver than just goes even more nuts.

deck_name: My dragon maids with their daddies
deck_excerpt: I want to build a dragon deck and this is the best i"ve found
deck_description:
Dragon maid+ Dragon daddies. This version was made by

El Exordio del Duelista.
Mi deck puede que este mal o este bien, pero a mi me parece que esta bien

While Megalith loses in modern and the high pointed card in genesys hurts your play, in Common Chairty format the deck is one of a few tier 1 decks, able to compete and outgrind with the other 3 top decks: Melodious, Lunalight, and Tenyi. And witht the advent of the mulcharmies and droplet into the format your ability to break a board or draw outs against other decks has only gotten better. Setting up a quick Behthor backed by hand traps and a tribute off Anastasis is enough to stop or break most other boards with the ability to Phaleg on the following turn to otk.

deck_excerpt: Regenesis Dogmatika is GENESYS' best grindy control advantage deck!
deck_description:
Regenesis Dogmatika is GENESYS' best grindy control advantage deck!

Regenesis is very simple to play and it has no combos, so I'm not making a detailed strategy guide on it. Just use the handtraps, simplify your opponent's gamestate, then outgrind them with your relentless Regenesis deck core! Even your Regenesis monsters get sent to the graveyard during your opponent's turn, they all just return to your hand in the endphase, and their spells like "Regenesis" and "Code" can ressurect your monsters from the GY and Banishment! Not to mention that every single Regenesis monster is a massive beatstick, so you can also equalize your opponent's board in the battle phase by running everything over, especially with the 5000 ATK Regenesis Lord! The Dogmatika cards also grant additional power and synergy to the deck, since the many forms of Fleurdelis are 2500ATK/2500DEF, making them a perfect fit for the strategy! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF DUELISTS!

deck_excerpt: Dragon, Blue Eyes, Red Eyes, Primite, Bystial, Control, Handtrap Control
deck_description:
Goes first but doesn't mind going second.

Control deck with Bystials, Red Eyes Metal dragon stuff and Primite with Blue Eyes. If you time your interactions right, the deck can win almost against anything. But of course against the top meta decks you are in an uphill battle.

Optimal Endboard: Seals, Blue Eyes White Dragon + Primite Stuff or Seals , Max Metamorph. In some hands you can achieve all of it but not always.

Deck can brick going first. It happens very rarely. You can still win those games because you bricking means you drew bunch of handtraps.

deck_excerpt: Learn how to use Miracle Raven in the Megalith deck.
deck_description:
---------------------------Combos with Miracle Raven:

 

Note: I made these combos without using Megalith Emergence, but later realized it's essential to use it in the main deck, so at the end of the combo you just need to use Phuloch effect to Ritual Hagith from GY to add Emergence.

 

Place the continuation of the link on the duelingbook.com website

 

replay?id=813757-76589021

Combo 1: Raven + Unformed + any monster

Note: You perform the Anastasis + Chalislime combo

 

replay?id=813757-76589351

Combo 2: Bethor + Ophiel + Raven + any monster

Note: You perform the Chalislime + Phul combo

 

replay?id=813757-76590777

Combo 3: 2x Miracle Raven + any normal summon

Note: You perform the Chalislime + Phul combo

 

replay?id=813757-76591288

Combo 4: Miracle Raven + Benten

Note: You perform the Chalislime + Phul combo, adding Benten to your hand instead of the Unformed monster. Chalislime.

 

replay?id=813757-76588066

Combo 5: Chalislime + Raven + any Normal Summon + discard

 

---------------------------Some Test Hands with Miracle Raven:

 

replay?id=813757-76598045

Test Hand 1: 2x Miracle Raven + Bethor + Phuloch + Penciplume

 

replay?id=813757-76590480

Test Hand 2: Raven + 2x Unformed + Hagith + Ash Blossom

Note: You do the Chalislime + Phul combo

 

In this combo I made the mistake of using Phul's effect twice; it should have been Bethor instead, which would have given me one less random card in my hand. I could have simply used Inception to Ritual Summon Hagith and discard Bethor with Anastasis's effect, but I got confused in that part and... The replay got confusing from that point on, but that would be the only difference.

 

I hope this helped you get the most out of Miracle Raven in Megalith.

deck_excerpt: Ft. Buio+Mutiny in the sky for more fusion summons :)
deck_description:
Going first Musketeers with Buio the Dawn's light, very easy to dump with Aerial eater to search Mutiny in the Sky.

Mutiny can also be used to summon Duke of Demise for some funky combo lines and sometimes another Musketeer normal summon.

Went for a more handtrap focused list, not my favorite, but this format pretty much demands it...

You could still play cards like Fiendsmith in Paradise+the Unchained engine for a better turn 1 board. But that also makes going second harder.

Video below for some Musket action :)

deck_excerpt: blue-eyes Fiendsmith bystial link syncho Team_VRW
deck_description:
This build combines the explosive pressure of Blue-Eyes with the consistency and resource looping of the Fiendsmith engine. The deck centers around Chain Resonator as a searchable bridge piece through Wishes for Eyes of Blue and Sage, giving it multiple reliable starters and tuners. The Blue-Eyes package provides strong bodies, recursion, and access to Synchro lines—while Neo Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon serves exclusively as a Graveyard negate and as an equip target for the Contact Fusion into Blue-Eyes Tyrant Dragon, never needing to be summoned.

The Fiendsmith engine adds depth to the strategy through its powerful recycling and toolbox potential. Cards like Fiendsmith Engraver, Kyrie, and Desirae allow the deck to recover resources, extend plays, and maintain pressure even after disruption. Combined with a robust hand trap lineup and utility spells such as Triple Tactics Talent and Crossout Designator, the deck adapts smoothly to going first or second.

Side Deck Strategy

 

The Side Deck is designed to broaden the deck’s answers against diverse matchups. Cards like Artifact Lancea, Dark Ruler No More, and Super Polymerization help break established boards or shut down resource-heavy engines. Additional Mulcharmy cards and Gravity Collapse provide alternative interruption lines, while tech options like Sales Ban and Ty-Phon give situational coverage. Overall, the Side Deck focuses on improving the deck’s ability to handle high-tempo strategies and resilient combo engines.

The deck is designed to offer several reliable starters, flexible combo routes, and consistent interruption points. By combining tuners, extenders, and searchable lines, the deck aims to create a stable end board with negations while still maintaining the Blue-Eyes identity and playstyle. This hybrid approach increases both resilience and adaptability, making it capable of responding to various matchups throughout the duel.

deck_excerpt: "This legendary dragon is a powerful engine of destruction. Virtually invincible, very few have faced."
deck_description:
"This legendary dragon is a powerful engine of destruction. Virtually invincible, very few have faced this awesome creature and lived to tell the tale." - Blue-Eyes flavour text

Blue-Eyes is one of those decks that have aged beautifully in Masterduel's meta! Kaiba's ace strategy is definitely still playable and easily winnable in the cutthroat ladder games even during December 2025! 
 
Already powerful with the structure deck support, Blue-Eyes White Dragon is propelled into even higher heights of power with the introduction of the Primite cards! Primite adds a whole new layer of interruption, advantage, starters and recursion to the Blue-Eyes strategy. Ether Beryl searches sets your Primite spells from deck while being a level 4 Dragon which can be linked into Spirit with Eyes of Blue. Lordly Lode searches for Primite cards, while being an extender for any normal monster, most notably Blue-Eyes White Dragon. Finally, Drillbeam's potent targeted negate banish is a powerful interruption that also resets itself every turn! 
 
Able to play low to the ground in simplified gamestates due to Maxx "C" or mass handtraps, Blue-Eyes Primite can still have a respectable board even when interrupted. On the other hand, Blue-Eyes Primite's best board is extremely hard to crack, especially with Drillbeam protecting your massive Dragons!
 
The immense advantage that this 7 card engine makes Blue-Eyes nearly unstoppable in Masterduel ladder when piloted properly! Now you get to dominant the duel arena just like Kaiba did in Battle City as the world's (second) strongest duelist!

GLHF duelists!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Earlier today, I published episode 90 of Yu-Gi-Oh! Progression Maniac, where I opened a box of Toon Chaos and 16 packs of Legendary Duelists: Season 1. This profile is the final form of Episode 90's deck, after changing deck themes twice. Let me know what you think of this deck in the comments, and check out my video below when you can.

This is Yami Yugi deck he used in the 2nd season of the Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Monsters anime (Battle City arc).

Are you a fan of 5D's? Ever wanted to summon beautiful women who also happened to be dragons? Tired of all the violence in life? This deck may just be for you.

A recreation of the deck I have. You may notice that there's only one Life Dragon! This is because I am POOR. I will absolutely recommend running another one. You can definitely cut the Crimson Dragon and any other cards related to it (Level 12s), because the likelyhood of going into it is not that big!!

Other than that, this Deck will be your ever faithful companion for when you plan to climb the lawless land that is Rookie - Bronze - Silver and Gold. And, if you believe in it enough, maybe Platinum. Anything further and you may find that it is unfortunately not that consistent and not that strong. Regardless, Ancient Fairy Dragon has always been a card I adored deeply, so this deck was definitely a must-have for me.

As you may be able to tell, I am not the best at Deck Building, however, I do want Ancient Fairy Dragon to be the star of the show and not just a one-off in a different deck like Blue-Eyes that you go into if you feel like it.

On its best days, it is absolutely capable of filling the board with both Ancient Fairy Versions, Stardust, Dis Pater or Chaos Angel, Crystal Wing, Arc Light and Eternal Sunshine if you play your card rights.

On its worst, the board will be a real stinker consistent of one LIGHT Beast and nothing else.

Anyways, I hope someone finds as much joy in this deck as I have

Going first build, but has good going-second gas (I mean, it's Mikanko). Mikanko is getting harder to play into the meta, so we're bringing back a few locks with El Shaddoll Winda and Metalsilver Armor. Going first you want to set up typical Mikanko disurptions: Rivalry (typically equipping Angelica's Angelic Ring or Metalsilver on opponent's turn), Spiritwalk, Ohime (typically equipping Reflection Rondo on opponent's turn), along with Droplet, and additional handtraps.

I'm still unsure of keeping the Kaiju or Ultimate Slayer, but in the best-of-1 format the game's a gamble and it's good to have some clearing power going 2nd.

deck_excerpt: The next evolution in fusion technology is finally here in Masterduel, and it is Dracotail! Time to combine it with Branded!
deck_description:
The next evolution in fusion technology is finally here in Masterduel, and it is Dracotail! These spellcaster dragons do relatively few actions for a lot of impact! Everytime you fusion summon with Dracotail monsters, can set a Dracotail spell/trap from deck, then get an additional effect which breaks your opponent's board, giving this strategy inherent board breaking capabilities. Dracotail Faimena can also fusion summon as a quick effect during the Main Phase, meaning you can fusion summon turn 0 and immediately start interrupting your opponent! This low amount of special summons Dracotail does allows it to perfectly play in Maxx "C," creating a lot of advantage and interruptions while minimizing the amount of draws your opponent gets. 

Paired with Branded, Dracotail becomes near unstoppable! Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! This strategy generates a ton of massive beatsticks on field, smashes through established boards with in-engine cards, and generates a ton of advantage! Albax and Phryxul has truly made the ultimate fusion strategy!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Lightning Warrior OTK ft. Telefon + Nature's Reflection
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will keep lots of cards in hand to splash down the opponent. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Activate "Black Garden" to plant two flowers to opposing side and replace "Black Garden" with "Dice Dungeon" later on. Meanwhile, keep as many cards in your hand as you can.

2) Synchro Summon 2 x Lightning Warrior cards and gift them to your opponent with "Mystic Box". In order to summon them, shuffle Stardust with Emeral at some point and do the followings:

  • Librarian + Telefon => Stardust + Telefon = Lightning Warrior
  • Monster Reborn   >>> Stardust + Telefon = Lightning Warrior

3) Play Burning >>> Broken/Golden combo to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1. Also, activate "Infinite Cards" to not discard your huge hand at End Phase. In addition, set your Traps and end your turn.

4) When it's Draw Phase, activate both Traps. Unleashed forces your opponent to attack with monsters and Reflection will direct damage Lightning would cause right back at your opponent.

5) When it's Battle Phase, both Lightning Warriors will attack and destroy your monsters. However, with what was explained in #4, your opponent will be exploded...

  • As the element of surprise, you can plan your timing of "Nature's Reflection" but you have to activate Unleashed at Draw Phase. Keep them in mind.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" can be collected by completing the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Machine Duplication" can be either found within "Rescue Team, Emergency Dispatch!" or "Roid Nexus" Secret Packs to save 90 SR!

- "Synchro Creed" can be found within "Radiant Inferno" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Relinquished Anima" can be either found within "Tales of the Witch" or "Toontastic" Secret Packs to save 30 UR!

- "Mecha Phantom Beast Auroradon" can be found within "Rapid Aircraft Advancement" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Daigusto Emeral" can be found within "Ties to Mother Nature" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Chicken Game" can be found within "The Most Dangerous Race of the Cosmos!" Secret Pack to save 90 UR!

- "Golden Bamboo Sword" can be found within "A Dance Dedicated to the Heavens" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- These following cards can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 300 SR:

  • 1 x Ravenous >>> 30 SR
  • 3 x Dice Dungeon >>> 90 SR
  • 3 x Ancient Leaf >>> 90 SR
  • 3 x Dimension Dice >>> 90 SR

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 240 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!
Radiant Typhoon

05.12.2025
Genesys Tournament, 6 Players



Round 1 vs Primite Eldlich:

I went second, we played a 50 minute game 1, time was called in Turn 6 or 8 or something, he gave me the win because I had a lethal line.
His board on Turn 1 was Drillbeam, Snake-Eye Vengance Dragon and 2 Eldlich Traps as disruption, played through the board and on the grind. Chaotic Elements in grind game is crazy.

Round 2 vs Kewl Tune:

Could have won Game 1 going first with Queen of the Blazing Domain, but I played kind of fast because it was 30 mins again, so I did couple of misplays and lost. Game 2 was quick loss.

Round 3 vs Infernoble, Rongo Turbo.

I won DR, couldnt play through interrupts and Queen, never made Rongo and lost 2-0.

 

overall I thought I would go 0 - X, but ashened is actually not that bad in Genesys.

Kind of sad you need to pay 33 for Flame Banshee but its fine. I played a lot of charmies because they make Rank 4s,
which came up twice. Also won two games with Castel. Wouldnt change much about the list, if any.
Final Bringer could also be Fallen and The Virtuous if you want, its nice to just have a backrow that can pop Veidos if needed.
I play 2 ashened for eternity for better grind. its so sad the card only does that on activation...

Never used Slayer, Slicer or Trunade though, didnt draw them if I sided them.

deck_name: Locals: Radiant Typhoon FIRST PLACE UNDEFEATED out of 14     (06.12.2025)
deck_excerpt: Locals: Radiant Typhoon FIRST PLACE UNDEFEATED out of 14     (06.12.2025)
deck_description:
06.12.2025
TCG Tournament, 14 players.

MST best deck

Round 1 vs Blue-Eyes:
He was a newly returning player, he had no chance, 2-0.

Round 2 vs Labrynth Yubel
He was new at the deck, he had no chance, 2-0.

Round 3 vs Gem-Knight
Against one of our better players, but it was his second time on Gem-Knights.
He also was tilted and therefore made some mistakes, I still felt like I played super clean. 2-1.
Lost Game 2 because he drolled me, I chained Vision, and after it all resolves I had Chant, Swen, Swen, Eldam, Eldam and something else in Hand.
Made Caesar but he had an out of course.

Round 4 vs Mitsurugi Fiendsmith
Against one of our best players.

He went first Game 1, end board:
Murakumo,
Futso,
Purification,
I:P,
Lacrima + Desirae + Agmunday in GY setup,
Ash Blossom in hand.

He forgot I was on super poly, otherwise he said he would have made a different board,
so in draw I went prio on super poly, fuse the Mitsus to Garura, Purification completely offline, new chain Fonix to special, he didnt yet summon Desirae.
On Fonix summon, Chant to add Monster, Fonix shuffle back I:P and Purification so he also doesnt get Purification GY eff which is dangerous.
In Standby he made Desirae, in main I just go S:P, draw a card off Garura and out the Desirae.

He then ashed my swen but I had enough gas to keep going, get Krosea off Eldam and used Manifestation + MST to set up Fonix and Varuroon again.
(dont know the details of the game state any more but of course you can NOT Manifestation Chain MST, Mill Varuroon and then summon back Varuroon because of the MST, that is not legal, but as I said dont quite know game state any more, I also dont know if I still had something in hand or whatever.)
He also had no real followup because none of the Mitsus triggered and I negated his Engraver with Varuroon.

I set up my followup interruptions a little wrong because I had only MST set and not a RT quickplay but it was enough.

Game 2 he didnt draw a Mitsu play. He ended on Desirae + Ceasar, I used droplet only with monsters, and he didnt even chain something else and negate with Desirae, maybe because he forgot or didnt have a playable Spell/Trap (f.e. Purification was a dead backrow), so I got rid of his board super quickly and he again didnt have enough followup because he wasnt able to do any Misu things again.


Decklist:
I have barely changed the list in the last couple of weeks.

Main Deck is almost completely set in stone for now, the Fiendsmith engine to go for Ceasar is theoretically optional, but its so powerful I feel like its mandatory. Also really important against Dracotail because they have multiple monster effects that fuse and you usually dont want to use the MST+Trap on those.

In the extra, I rarely make Gossip Shadow Zeus, or with the FS even Totem Bird, but they should still be in the list I feel like. Gossip Shadow is just to break boards if they let me make a Rank 3, because an end board piece that lets the both players draw a card while I dont play handtraps is terrible.

For Fallen & The Virtuous, you can play Alba Lenatus instead of the 3rd Albion to make some people think youre actually on branded stuff :P. In this deck you could even play more targets because the Trap recycles Fallen & The Virtuous.

In the side deck, I side Charmies for going second,
Ash mostly for matchups because the only charmy that hurts is Purulia and barely anyone plays it right now. I just played it to try it, never drew it.
Droll for certain matchups, didnt side against Mitsu FS because of the FS part so if they have a good hand its just a -1.
Tenki for going first to brick less, but plays into droll sadly.
Judgement for breakers going first and Yummy and Warning also for Yummy.

Didnt play an our for Liger because noones on Lunalight at my locals right now. I would play Lava Golem if I needed an out probably.

 

All in all, 4-0, lost one Duel total, and im super happy. I dont get why I dont see this deck more in the TCG, the deck is crazy, even before the busted support the will come out in Burst Protocol, and super fun because you get to annihalate boards in the draw phase. nice Snatchy, nice I:P, nice Forced Release, Idiots :D.

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes may have much attack, but Dark Magician got all the powerful Spells and Traps!
deck_description:
A competitive version of the Dark Magician deck. It focuses on utilizing monsters able to Special Summon themselves after having used Songs of the Dominators from the hand. The deck can also easily use the Horus engine, either for setting up protection before going into Dark Magician of Destruction, or go into it itself.

The Extra Deck is rather flexible, and can be tailored to counter the available meta. With such a flexible Extra Deck, I would recommend using Ultimate Slayer and/or Metaltronus to counter the current meta. For Metaltronus specifically, S:P Little Knight and Magician's Rod both are Dark monsters with 1600 ATK, making it a good counter against most stratergies commonly summoning S:P Little Knight. 

The Side Deck currently plays Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Droll & Lock Bird, which goes against the Dominus Traps that the deck is based around. These are primarily against any Mulcharmy you're hit by, but since the deck *can* play through them without giving your opponent too many draws, I would recommend changing these out to stronger board breakers such as Super Polymerization and other targeted counters against the meta.

deck_excerpt: Mitsurugi Exodia deck based on FTK Combo Video I saw
deck_description:
Funny deck based on video from Bob the Duelist. Pretty consistent (probably 4/5 hands lead to ftk). Can just play mitsu the rest of the time (with 7 extra bricks). Not terrible (could probably take a local) but not great either. Pure Mitsu is definitely better, but this is way funnier (and more hype).

Note: FTK dies to every handtrap in the game, hence called by and crossout. If you get hand trapped, just switch to playing mitsu.

Note2: Fusions are just prosp targets. Change them out for whatever. Can also run extrav (in which case, run as many duplicates of the central cards as you can), but it feels worse, since it is a one card ftk (just need habakiri).

Jack Atlas character deck with a guest appearance of Bystial Dis Pater.  

Savior Demons Dragon (Majestic Red Dragon) cut due to the majority of "Majestic" support being Yusei centric.  Dark Highlander works counter productive to the deck, and Celestial Wolf Sirius doesn't work for this domain.  Crimson Blader I passed up due to being subpar given the deck's focus on dragon support, and Demon Chaos King (Chaos King Archfiend) I don't like to count since Jack just borrowed the card once.  I do count Stardust Dragon though since Jack in lore stole it and used it for years and against Yusei before Yusei got it back.

Bonus round:  Jack cards from the manga and Arc-V because there can only be one king, and it's Jack.

PUNK P.U.N.K. Earthbound Immortal

Lightning Storm can be whatever, its just a fun go second card for the Greater Linewalker+Uru line. (So 5 flex slots)

deck_excerpt: A deck I cooked up for club play
For Christmas you get a removed Extra
Going second varient of Gate Guardians
Using Mitsurugi acts as bait for the Time Thief play.
deck_description:
Main 2 card combo: Time Thief Regulator and Ame no Habakiri no Mitsurugi / Mitsurugi Prayers 

  1. Activate either Mitsurugi as bait for Ash.
  2. Normal Summon Regulator.
  3. Regulator effect, tribute itself, Special Summon Time Thief Winder and Time Thief Adjuster.
  4. Winder CL1 search Time Thief Retrograde, Adjuster CL2 send Time Thief Bezel Ship to GY.
  5. Xyz into anything necessary.

Bridging from Time Thief to Mitsurugi: King of the Feral Imps detach 1 to search Habakiri.

Bridging from Mitsurugi to Time Thief:

  1. Link Summon Silhouhatte Rabbit, set Time Thief Power Reserve.
  2. Xyz Summon Number 60: Dugares the Timeless, detach 2 to draw 2 & discard 1.
  3. Xyz Xyz Armor Fortress using Dugares, detach 1 to search Full-Armored Xyz, set.
  4. On opponent's turn
    • Activate Power Reserve, Special Summon itself and other Time Thief.
    • Activate Full-Armored Xyz to Xyz Summon Redoer.

Handtraps and Extra Decks can be customized depending on the format.
This decks uses azamina and dominus impulse

Creator: Gabriel Silva da Silva

Tournament: Manaus WCQ Regional – December 7th 2025

Placement: Top 4

Thanks for Leprechaun Shaun for the HEAVY Inspiration.

(Basically made it more similar to my OCG Deck)

Waiter! Waiter! More engines please!

The Libromancers help set up the main combo lines, gives you a link 2, and sets up 1 negate without using your normal summon: Use the libromancers to search each other + Doombroker, then link off the libromancers on board to special summon ASHLAUN U1000, use ASHLAUN's effect to reveal Doombroker and search Cyber Angel Benten.  Activate Libromancer First Appearance to ritual summon Doombroker using Benten, then use Benten's effect to search Diviner of the Herald.  Now use Doombrokers effect to set Libromancer Intervention from your deck to one of your center 3 spell & trap zones.  

Now heres the main line:

  1. Normal Summon Diviner sending Herald of the Arc Light, then use Arc Light to search Ame no Habakiri no Mitsurugi.  
  2. Use Habakiri's effect to special Mitsurugi no Mikoto, Saji from your deck and tribute your Diviner.  Use Diviner's effect to special summon Poissonniere de Nouvelles from deck, then chain Saji's effect to search Mitsurugi Ritual from deck.  Use Poissonniere's effect to search Nouvelles Recipe Book from your deck.  
  3. Activate Mitsurugi Ritual's 2nd effect to special summon Habakiri sending Mitsurugi no Mikoto, Kusanagi and Night Sword Serpant from your deck to the GY.  Activate Kusanagi targetting Mitsurugi Ritual, then activate Night Sword Serpant's effect to special itself.  
  4. Activate Recipe Book.  Then, activate Mitsurugi Ritual's 1st effect to special summon Ame no Murakumo no Mitsurugi from deck by tributing Habakiri on field.  Activate Recipe Book targetting Murakumo to search Chef de Nouvelles, then activate Habakiri's effect in grave to search Mitsurugi Great Purification from deck and to special summon itself.  Set Purification in one of the center 3 spell & trap zones.  
  5. (NOTE: you can do this before step 4 if you did the Libromancer combo to insulate against Nibiru, the Primal Being) XYZ summon Evilswarm Exciton Knight using Saji and Night Sword.  Link off Exciton to make Fiendsmith's Requiem,  then use Requiem's effect to special Lacrima the Crimson Tear's effect to send Fiendsmith Engraver from deck to GY. Use Lacrima + Habakiri to link summon Fiendsmith's Sequence.  Use Sequence's effect to fusion summon Aerial Eater using Exciton and Engraver as material.  Activate Aerial Eater's effect to send Engraver back to GY.  If you did the Libromancer line you can link off Sequence + ASHLAUN to make A Bao A Qu, the Lightless Shadow, otherwise make S:P Little Knight using Poissonniere + Sequence.  Use Engraver's effect returning Sequence to special summon himself.  Then, XYZ summon D/D/D Wave High King Caeser using Aerial Eater + Engraver.  (NOTE: you now have Lacrima in grave to special Requiem on your opponents turn, then use Requiem to summon Lacrima to send Fiendsmith in Paradise.  You can use Paradise to send Fiendsmith's Desirae for removal if needed).
  6. Now you can scale Chef and activate his effect to search whatever you need for beginning Nouvelles combo.

deck_excerpt: Chimera and Dracotail are GENESYS' foremost fusion strategies! Can they work well together? DEFINITELY!
deck_description:
Let's face it, Dracotail is pretty friggin' strong in the "lower power" format of GENESYS (I think it will get more points added in the next points update), where not much can contest the insane advantage engine that these spellcaster dragons can give to the duelist. Combine that with Chimera, and you'll find that yourself with an incredibly powerful fusion deck with a bazillion cards in hand, field and GY to overwhelm your opponent with sheer card advantage! 

Everytime you fusion summon with Dracotail monsters, can set a Dracotail spell/trap from deck, then get an additional effect which breaks your opponent's board, giving this strategy inherent board breaking capabilities. Dracotail Faimena can also fusion summon as a quick effect during the Main Phase, meaning you can fusion summon turn 0 and immediately start interrupting your opponent! Arthalion and Secreterion can also recycle your powerful monsters from the field and GY as well, ensuring you can a near infinite grindgame!

Chimera is an incredible advantage engine capable of overwhelming your opponent with so much resources, interactions and draw power - represented in a fusion deck! For example, one Mirror Swordknight is a whopping +7 in card advantage! While in GENESYS it loses out on some consistency with Cornfield Coatl costing a whopping 33 points, the strategy is still competent in this format's power vacuum giving the duelist incredible boss monsters such as Diabellze (anti-spell) and Guardian Chimera (draw and destroy big beatstick). 

Combined together, this fusion of these two powerful archetypes can obliterate any opposing strategy in GENESYS!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
Mermail Atlantean

deck_excerpt: Sling spells and hope your opponent doesn't draw Droll
deck_description:
This deck has a simple, straightforward gameplay loop: summon medius, make Diactorus, and then profit.

This deck also features the card Theorealize  to better leverage the Fiendsmith engine. By sending Medius the Pure  to the grave, you can summon him out, summon the Artmage Power Patron , and make Artmage Diactorus  before changing Diactorus into a Light Fiend with the graveyard effect of Theorealize. From there it's simply:

Make Fiendsmith's Requiem > Requiem Summon Lacrima the Crimson Tears  > Lacrima foolish Fiendsmith Engraver  > Requiem effect equip to Lacrima > make Necroquip Princess  > summon Engraver > make D/D/D Wave High King Caesar .

The Artmage combo is well-defined and shown in plenty of videos and guides, so I won't cover it myself, but some important notes I like to make include:

  • When completing the Artmage line, you often progress through Graflare > Litera > and Artmage Finmel . If you have gone uninterrupted, I like to make Cross-Sheep  with Graflare and Litera pointing to Diactorus before summoning Finmel. This allows you to summon Finmel to the zone and reborn the Litera, which means on your opponent's turn you can use Litera effect to summon either the patron or the Artmage Graflare , depending on which you need. This is best applied when you are able to set Artmage Masterwork -Succession- to further leverage the Cross-sheep to increase your advantage even further.
  • It is important to note that the graveyard effect of Artmage Pact -Awakening- works well when you are able to use it with Artmage Litera . Litera's effect uses the "then" clause, meaning if you go chain link 1 Litera, chain link 2 -Awakening-, you get to summon off of Litera and the pop off of Awakening while only bouncing one monster to hand.
  • Don't forget your extra normal summon from Artmage Academic Arcane Arts Acropolis for Medius the Pure as that can help you, especially when playing into boards. 
  • There are a few substitutions that you can make in the extra deck, and I'd like to list a few of the cards worth consideration below:
    • a Moon of the Closed Heaven is still legal in Master Duel, so that is a worthwhile inclusion. However, because of the lock applied by the fieldspell, you are unlikely to make it mid-combo or to pivot to it at the end of your combo. For now, I am playing Cross-Sheep over Moon for this reason.
    • You are able to make rank 4 monsters using Medius and Lacrima, or by using two copies of Medius. For this reason, you can consider playing Gallant Granite or King of the Feral Imps to search Nibiru, the Primal Being or Ame no Habakiri no Mitsurugi if you decide to include those cards in your builds.

This deck's major weaknesses are Droll & Lock Bird and Nibiru, the Primal Being (if you do not see Fiendsmith cards). Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring on your Medius the Pure can also stop your turn if you do not see an extender. For these reasons, it is always best to lead the Fiendsmith engine to draw out as many handtraps as possible before attempting to resolve Medius.

IN CONCLUSION, I love this deck! I am very happy to see it coming to Master Duel (finally) and hope you have fun playing it as well. This is just one build of the deck, and it has many other engines and sub-engines that can assist with its gameplan. Don't shy away from experimentation!

deck_excerpt: The best final countdown deck that I think is possible, copied and edited for TCG from a master duel guy.
deck_description:
Gameplan

1) Bring forth Tethys by replacing Capricious/Aces/Corobane and draw your whole deck...

  • Whenever you draw a Fairy, reveal it to draw another card with Tethys. You can keep it going until you can't draw anymore.
  • If you hit non-Fairy, you stop movement. So, continue with Ixchel and alike to trigger Tethys again.
  • Always use "Arcana Force XV" in-hand to fetch what would be otherwise brick by Tethys, which is "Light Barrier".
  • Know that card draw has to be caused by an effect, not as cost, in order to draw a card with Tethys. For example, using "Upstart Goblin", seen in Side Deck, won't do any help for Tethys but "Into the Void" will. Remember this rule well.

2) If Tethys + Aces are together, Link Summon Insulator with them. Otherwise, place Rain and Lebellman onto Pendulum Zones to Pendulum Summon 2 x Carbon + Capricious + Orange. Also, activate "Final Countdown" and "Light Barrier".

3) XYZ Summon Starring Knight with 2 x Carbon as materials. Then, use Knight to Special Summon The World and pick the outcome as heads thanks to "Light Barrier" to be able to skip your opponent's turn by sending two monsters you control to GY.

4) Synchro Summon Chaos Beast with Capricious + Orange. At that moment, Carbon asks you to shuffle itself on top of your Main Deck, which is essential to not deck-out for 20 turns forward.

5) End your turn and use The World to send Beast + Knight to GY, in order to be able to do what was explained in #3. When it's your move, bring forth Carbon + Beast for The World and repeat until you win with Final Countdown...

  • With many LIGHT and DARK monsters available at your arsenal, reviving Beast won't be an issue, provided that you use Beast to retrieve banished monsters into your hand. Afterwards, Pendulum Summon them and use these as resources for The World.
  • No matter what you do, don't forget to send Carbon to GY for The World at all costs to not deck-out by accident.

THE MAN is ready to send Duelist Cup participants into the Shadow Realm!
deck_description:
The Man With the Mark - Odion, has certainly "hit the mark" in the competitive Masterduel scene! The latest Masterduel Selection Pack "Aerial Superiority" has been a massive boon for this seemingly forgotten Ishtar sibling, granting Odion a powerful combo trap deck! Able to play comfortably into Maxx C, Mulcharmies, Droll, Nibiru and even Dimension Shifter, while being ultra consistent and packing 20+ staple slots... Odion's strategy has surprisingly been incredibly competent even in the hyper competitive Duelist Cup defeating the likes of Dracotail, Mitsurugi and Maliss!

Not only do you get to spam the field repeatedly with 2-3 Apophis the Swamp Deity's omni-negates, when paired with Statue of Anguish Pattern all these trap monsters become "pops!" All these cards are searchable and summonable turn 1 thanks to Odion's signature strategy, activating trap cards the same turn they were set with "Temple of the Kings," another iconic piece of Yugioh anime history now suddenly made competitive! 

How about going second? Due to the extremely consistent nature of Odion's strategy (Anubis, Man with Mark, Treasures of the King and Serket all kind of searches each other), you can play this deck with 21 staple cards without bricking!

First it was Ishizu responsible for creating the strongest Yugioh deck of all time, Ishizu Tearlament... Now is it Odion's turn to dominate competition like he did in Battle City?

Here is the main combo for the deck:

Man with the Mark + 1 card to set = Apophis the Swamp Deity (omni-negate), 
  1. Normal summon Man with the Mark. Search Treasures of the Kings.
  2. Activate Treasures of the Kings and set from deck Apophis the Serpent.
  3. Set another card from your hand in the backrow. 
  4. Activate Treasure of the King's effect to search for Merciless Scorpion of Serket from deck. 
  5. Summon Serket by banishing a level 10 (usually Nibiru) from deck. 
  6. Activate Serket's effect to search for Temple of the Kings from deck. 
  7. Activate Temple of the Kings.
  8. Activate Apophis the Serpent to summon itself and set Apophis the Swamp Deity from deck. 
  9. XYZ summon Gallant Granite using Man with the Mark + Apophis the Serpent.
  10. Detach Apophis the Serpent from Gallant Granite to search for Lord of the Heavenly Prison from deck. 
  11. Activate Lord of the Heavenly Prison's effect to reveal itself and to protect your face-down cards.
  12. Activate Apophis the Serpents trigger effect in the GY to search for Embodiment of Apophis from deck. 
  13. Link summon Silhouhatte Rabbit and set from deck Statue of Anguish Pattern.
  14. Set your cards in the backrow, especially the Embodiment of Apophis you searched. 
  15. As soon as possible during your opponent's turn, activate Statue of Anguish Pattern to summon it. 
  16. Activate Lord of the Heavenly Prison's trigger effect to summon itself from hand and set any trap card from deck (usually Verdict of Anubis).
GLHF Duelists!
 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Narwhal FTK ft. Centrifugal Field + Dragon Knight
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, we will use an unorthodox method to burn your opponent with Narwhal thanks to interaction between "Centrifugal Field" and "Dragon Knight" cards. Let's see them in action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Synchro Summon Narwhal with Slime + Coral as materials and place it to a very safe place. Meanwhile, place Dissolver on Pendulum Zone.

2) Special Summon Yajiro with Saryuja and pass it to the opponent with "Shien's Spy". Clear at least two places with Coral/Ravenous/Legatia, if needed.

3) Activate "Centrifugal Field" first and Dissolver after. There, Fusion Summon "Dark Magician the Dragon Knight" with Hex + Saryuja as materials and put it to where Yajiro would pop it.

4) After Yajiro pops Dragon Knight, Narwhal starts blasting your opponent. To make it a loop, "Centrifgual Field" is here to revive Dragon Knight thanks to two facts...

  • You have to revive a Fusion material named on Fusion monster. In the case of "Dark Magician the Dragon Knight", it's "Dark Magician".
  • Since Dragon Knight is also named as "Dark Magician" while in GY, Centrifugal picks up "Dark Magician" which is Dragon Knight.

5) Repeating what was explained in #3 and #4 is what you need to win the game!

deck_excerpt: The simple, straightforward but potent midrange playstyle of Dracotail is now yours to yield in Masterduel!
deck_description:
With the release of Masterduel's newest Selection Pack "Aerial Superiority," ladder has changed forever with Dracotail's introduction to the arena! 

Everytime you fusion summon with Dracotail monsters, can set a Dracotail spell/trap from deck, then get an additional effect which breaks your opponent's board, giving this strategy inherent board breaking capabilities. Dracotail Faimena can also fusion summon as a quick effect during the Main Phase, meaning you can fusion summon turn 0 and immediately start interrupting your opponent! Arthalion and Secreterion can also recycle your powerful monsters from the field and GY as well, ensuring you can a near infinite grindgame!

This build of Dracotail features a whopping 19 handtraps! Theoretically, your opponent would be hardpressed to play through all those handtraps, then Dracotail can smash through any "half-board" they would make. The interruptions Dracotail can make with it's three traps (1 bounce of ATK position monster, 1 spell negate, 1 GY banish, 1 pop with Gulamel, 1 fuse with Faimena) backed by handtraps are also very difficult for any meta deck to play through. The game boils down to proper usage of handtraps and interruptions - forcing a simplified gamestate where the superior Dracotail engine can flourish!

The simple, straightforward but potent midrange playstyle of Dracotail is now yours to yield - the dominant strategy on ladder!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Branded post-December list. Small Shaddoll engine.
White Forest in Genesys; a new challenger appears.
deck_description:
White Forest list following the points update for Genesys

We no longer need to use 35-40 points on 3x crossout + droll 1/2 copies, as our nemesis has been vanquished. 

So although Azamina is almost totally off limits due to extreme point costs, we can focus on the core two expensive cards that are in my view non negotiable (Elzette Azamina and Diabell Queen of of the White Forest), at 47 points, and then build around that. 

Hand traps are difficult to fit in this deck although arguably a wider suite of these is preferable to 3 chicken game, however I think the card is extremely broken in White Forest going first so will be testing it out - this may be replaced by Fuwalos or similar after testing (or possibly 2x Forbidden Droplet). 

Points are : 3 Chicken Game (21), 2 Black Goat Laughs (20), 2 Nibiru (12) for a total of 53. 

Black Goat Laughs is worse without Foolish Burial Goods, but it is still the most potent discard with Elzette going second and is a card that is strong going first too as a set. 

Astellar is at 3 as its our strongest normal summon in a format with barely any imperm or veiler. Toy Box engine is excellent first or second even in a format where MST.deck is so potent. 

For extra deck, the other options I have considered are Zapper Shrimp + Satellite Warrior, or Genex Arms Zero and the dark level 6 synchro tuner that enables it. Nibiru is still scary, so I am testing Muddy Mudragon into Mechaba as an out to it or at least a line that forces a Nib earlier than the end of main. 

Side deck is what I've been testing the last month; Subdual into Diabellze often just FTKs Radiant Typhoon or other quick play decks and is still good v other decks that use spells, I like siding in Morrian going first and have Reframing in the side for decks that I think will bring in Evenly matched, although Scourge is a main decked card that can help here too. Of all the going second cards that still suit WF, I have found that 3 dark ruler in main backed with 3 swords of concealing light and 3 fusion tag works best. Concealing is very good in this deck as you can book the board and then send it for WF cost. And Fusion Tag turns any monster on board into Saint Azamina so you can tribute off any monster your opponent controls (even towers) for Azamina. 

Gravity Collapse is probably optimal here but I just find that card to be boring when playing locals or with friends. Synchro Zone is a semi floodgate but is good in synchro decks too for its other effects. 

Final word is on how good Diabellstar Vengeance is. being able to pop a card, then either summon a book of eclipse in Silvera or Poplar to then place two WF in backrow, and quick synchro into Snake Eye Vengeance Dragon is excellent. And you can then follow that up with summoning Snake Eye Doomed Dragon which deals with 1 card, 1 monster in backrow, pop a cont spell + a monster in BP with Vengeance, and another monster placed in backrow with Doomed. 

I think in a post droll environment this deck can thrive, but it still has its old weaknesses plus it can brick or draw awkward hands. I think this version could maybe be optimised by dropping chicken game for hand traps or droplets, but this is what I'll be testing for now. Only thought is whether we add something like Sphere Mode to the side and deal with the lack of a NS for horrible going second boards like Artmage.

deck_excerpt: a deck for one and only one thing, a guaranteed 2 card ftk.
deck_description: a deck for one and only one thing, a guaranteed 2 card ftk

Taking heavy inspiration from "Deepsea Darew" https://youtu.be/txBe_qL44ro?si=prUxeWhuAQkeFnuU

We do go first if we get the option to, you can't combo off as often like a traditional ghoti deck would but going first set's up your combo on the opponents turn and if you play the in-built interruption properly Lupine -> Banish 2 ghoti's -> pass can completly ruin some opponents if you have the hand "traps" for it.

Had to make some heavy changes to the original intent of the deck because of the point system. If you get lucky, you can summon a tuner and a non-tuner on the opponent's turn with several of these cards, and if I've done it right, there is a sychro for any combination of levels.

If we could play bystials we absolutely would but I decided that Purulia and searching Maxx"C" off Retaliating"C" is more consistent for this format. 

Side deck is full of situational "special summon during the opponents turn" cards to guarantee you have something relevant to the match-up.

Overall, very fun, probably not good enough. But maybe you cheese wins out of people who have no clue what you're doing :3

deck_excerpt: Hell hath no fury then a woman scorned.
deck_description: I have a Super Poly target just forgot to add it in the deck profile but feel free to add your own Super Poly target and be creative.
I love the E HEROes as a whole.

I still have not been playing that much Genesys, but when I do, I always load up with Gimmick Puppet because I just really like the Deck. The December 15th Points Update did hurt this Deck at all. If anything, Droll & Lock Bird going to 25 points means that we are no longer playing that card. Nibiru, the Primal Being going up a singular point is literally nothing. I have been messing around with different cards in the Main Deck ever since my previous list, and I have figured that this is pretty much what I want to see in the Main Deck: The Deck aims to blind second, it Main Decks a whole bunch of non-engine including going second cards, and we are just trying to interrupt the opponent's plays on their turn as much as possible to force them to end on a simplified board (more or less) in order to break through with whatever they have with your large Gimmick Puppet Xyz Monsters and inflicting damage whenever and wherever possible. It realy does help that Gimmick Puppet's Main Deck is not pointed at all except for Mansion of the Dreadful Dolls and the Rank-Up-Magics with Rank-Up-Magic Argent Chaos Force being the only RUM to be pointed at 5. Even so, with all of the pointed non-engine that I chose to play, I literally had like almost 20 to like 25 points left, which is why there are some interesting choices in cards that I am playing. 

For handtraps, we have 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ghost Mourner & Moonlit Chill, 3 Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, and 3 D.D. Crow. I am not playing Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion at all. While it is not too costly to play considering that it is only 5 points per copy, D.D. Crow kind of covers most of what Belle is meant to cover in all honesty. If you are using Belle offensively, you are trying to negate your opponent's effect that is either adding a card(s) from GY or Speical Summoning a Monster Card(s) from GY, and Crow covers both of these areas while being at 0 points. The only time I would probably play Belle over Crow is if I need to use Belle defensively, specifically to negate my opponent's D.D. Crow on one of my cards in the GY. While it would theoretically be wise to run Belle over Crow in Gimmick Puppet, a Deck that is subsceptible to Crow banishing one of your key cards in GY, I am purposefully choosing to play offensive handtraps to hit the opponent. At best, Belle is a Side Deckable card, but I feel that the cards that I am currently Side Decking are much more important than Belle. Nibiru is just a nice card all around, but do be careful about the interaction between popping the Primal Being Token with the effect of Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Hunter. Hunter detaches to target and destroy a card your opponent controls, and if it was sa monster, damage is inflicted to your opponent equal to its original ATK. The Primal Being Token's original ATK is ?, so its original ATK is treated as 0 and your opponent will not take any damage. Unless the Token is too big to run over, you are never using Giant Hunter's effect to pop the Token because Hunter can pop any card your opponent controls and possibly even deal a bunch burn damage if you destroyed a monster, so its effect wisely. Fuwalos is really nice because if you do draw cards off of it, you can draw into your multitude of non-engine. Actually, I would recommend playing Mulcharmy Purulia or even Mulcharmy Meowls because if you shift some points around, you can fit a playset of either in the Deck as well, and it helps you in the same way as Fuwalos does. Mourner negates a Special Summoned monster's effects and if that monster were to leave the field, your opponent takes damage equal to its original ATK, which is great to pair with the effects of your GImmick Puppet Xyz Monsters inflicting effect damage as well. Ghost Ogre is Ghost Ogre. It is really nice in a more limited format. 

For the Gimmick Puppet Main Deck Monsters, we have 1 Gimmick Puppet Bisque Doll, 3 Gimmick Puppet Rouge Doll, 1 Gimmick Puppet Dreary Doll, 1 Gimmick Puppet Cattle Scream, 3 Gimmick Puppet Little Soldiers, 1 Gimmick Puppet Scissor Arms, 2 Gimmick Puppet Terror Baby, and 1 Gimmick Puppet Fiendish Knight. I won't go into all of them in detail, but I'll explain their general purposes. Bisque Doll and Dreary Doll are terrible cards to open. They are more or less additional Level 8 Gimmick Puppet names in Deck for Rouge Doll to Summon or to dump into the GY with Condolence Puppet to use their GY effects. Normally, I would not play them, but they do help with protection (in the case of Bisque Doll) and extension (in the case of Dreary Doll). Rouge Doll in hand translates to 2 Level 8's on field. Cattle Scream is an extender and it gives a Gimmick Puppet Xyz Monster with it under it the effect to target and Special Summon a monster from your opponent's GY to their field, which can then be popped with any of your GImmick Puppet Xyz Monsters and burn your opponent. Little Soldiers dumps a Gimmick Puppet monster from Deck as cost and then makes its own Level equal to that monster's Level. It's GY effect can also help with turning your Level 4 Gimmick Puppets into Level 8's if necessary. Scissor Arms is just a worse version of Little Soliders, but it serves the same purpoe on field. It is probably the most cuttable one though. Terror Baby revives a Gimmick Puppet from GY in Defense on Normal Summon and its GY effect makes it so that your opponentcannot activate cards or effects in response to your Gimmick Puppet monster effects for the turn. Fiendish Knight is just a much better way to recurr Gimmick Puppet monsters from GY than Terror Baby and it can even recurr itself. 

Spell/Traps: 2 Rank-Up-Magic Argent Chaos Force. This is 10 points total for both copies, but I will explain. I had like 6 points still available, so I cut the Rank-Up-Magic Barian's Force I was intiially playing for a second copy of Argent Chaos Force. Argent Chaos Force is just the best RUM Spell for Gimmick Puppet. You can argue that Rank-Up-Magic Numeron Force is also really good. Yes, it can negate the effects of all other face-up cards on the field, but it can't Summon a CXyz monster. It can only make Number C monsters, and sometimes, you want to make an additional CXyz Gimmick Puppet Fanatix Machinix for its 3100 ATK instead of a crummy Giant Hunter with 2500 ATK (because that's all we get in this format due to Number 40: Gimmick Puppet of Strings and Number C40: Gimmick Puppet of Dark Strings being pointed at 50 each). Besides, you can recurr Argent Chaos Force multiple ways, either through its GY effect or through Gimmick Puppet Fantasix Machinix. 3 Piri Reis Map because we don't have Mansion to search for a Gimmick Puppet monster from Deck in this format. 3 Condolence Puppet which sends Gimmick Puppet names from Deck to GY up to the number of your opponent's monsters Special Summoned from the Extra Deck +1. Also, it has a GY effect to make a Machine Xyz Monster you control unable to be destroyed by your opponent's card effects while it is face-up on the field. 3 Dark Ruler No More. You could just play 2 and then cut like Scissor Arms to play 2 Final Bringer of the End Times or something. Finally, 1 Service Puppet Play which steals monsters your opponent controls up to the number of Gimmick Puppet Xyz Monsters you control and you can banish it from GY to target an Xyz in either GY and Summon it to either field.

Extra Deck: We are playing Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis because we had the extra points to do so. It does hurt your Fanatix Machinix, but Fanatix Machinix can be used as a beater at that point. 3 CXyz Gimmick Puppet Fanatix Machinix. Basically, it searches a Puppet Trap on Summon, it can detach 1 and Special Summon a monster from either GY to your opponent's field, and if a monster(s) is Special Summoned to your opponent's field, you can target 1 of them and destroy it, inflicting damage equal to half its orignal ATK. 3 Gimmick Puppet Fantasix Machinix which detaches 1 to add a RUM and give you an extra Normal Summon for a Machine. Also, it can being itself back to either field if you make a Gimmick Puppet Xyz and then you can add a RUM from GY to hand. 3 Number C15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Hunter which detaches 1 to target and pop a card your opponent controls, burning your opponent equal to a destroyed monster's original ATK if it destroys a monster. 3 Number 15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Grinder which can twice per turn detach a material during your Main Phase 1 to target and destroy a Special Summoned monster your opponent controls, inflicitng damage equal to its original ATK if that monster was an Xyz Monster. 2 Gimmick Puppet Gigantes Doll which can detach 2 to steal up to 2 of your opponent's monsters until the End Phase, locking you into Gimmick Puppet monsters and only being able to attack with Xyz Monsters. It can also Tribute itself to make all your monsters Level 8 for the turn. 

Side Decl: 3 Dogoran, the Mad Flame Kaiju which is just really good removal and it has a high ATK which can be helpful to pop and inflict damage with your Gimmick Puppet Xyz Monsters. Lava Golem also works, but it does prevent you from Normal Summoning, so unless you have a Rouge Doll to go into Fantasix Machinix, you can't rely on Little Soldiers or Scissor Arms to start your turn. 3 Shared Ride and 3 Mistaken Arrest. Shared Ride can be set going first to allow you to draw into handtraps on your opponent's turn whenever they search. Mistaken Arrest prevents both players from adding cards from Main Deck to hand until the end of your next turn after it is activated. You can literally recurr your Gimmick Puppets like Rouge Doll and Fiendish Knight from GY with Rouge Doll also Special Summoning from Deck. You aren't affected by this card at all. 3 Twin Twister for Spell/Trap removal. This could be Cosmic Cyclone instead if you want. 3 Solemn Judgment because we need some good cards to back up literally just a pop with Fanatix Machinix and maybe like 1 to 2 or 3 steals off of Service Puppet Play.

Usually ending off on either Yubel fusion or Yubel ultimate form.  Along with evil HERO fusions and chaos angel.  There's a lot to this deck and I recommend trying it out.  There's a million different combos.

First Attempt at Magikey with the Primite engine.  The sidedeck is currently cards I'm experimenting with.
Using the best things in Genesys to still make it work.

So it's decently fragile. Nasten does nothing half the time outside of being a body to summon off of Indulged to set up a fusion off of Dark Dance for Eveningstar, or to summon with Valhalla as a body on field. Ixchel is still a draw 2 and if you have Gulgalta in hand then that's a search to top it off.

 

I am 100% convinced that anyone running more than 1 Superbia and 1 Gulgalta is coping. That's not to say that either is particularly bad, it's moreso that this deck already has a problem with it's monsters doing nothing in hand (save for Ixchel) and very little in grave, and the ones you want in the grave do nothing in the hand except for being discard fodder for Condemned. Also, Superbia can't res. itself and can't proc it's res. off of a copied Contact since it misses timing.

 

Under the best possible circumstances you can get 1 spell negate, 1 monster negate, 1 monster steal, and a quick fusion into a board wipe. If you manage to also have Nasten or Ixchel on the endboard then that's another use of one of the traps, though it's usually better to just use them as fodder for the on-field activation of the traps.

 

Combo can be flexible, but getting to Eveningstar through any means possible is the number one priority since he not only grabs backrow but is also just a good endboard piece via copying Dark Dance in grave to summon First Darklord using a binned Morningstar. Generally you'll want to start by summoning Djehuty who then fetches Indulged, giving your opponent a Nasten or Ixchel and adding Superbia, Golgalta, or Morningstar to hand. Indulged + Kambi or Hecatrice discard for Valhalla into summoning any name in hand alongside Indulged or Djehuty will also do it. Either way, make Condemned, discard the added name off of Indulged and bin one of the others BUT absolutely make sure that Gulgalta and Morningstar are in rotation (Gulgalta summoned off of Djehuty into making Condemned using them is also viable). Gulgalta can add either Dark Dance or Banishment (Add banishment if you don't have Contact), then you can either summon Gulgalta if you have contact and fuse away one of the tokens + the Darklord on the opponent's field for Eveningstar or add Banishment, Banishment for Dark Dance, and hope you have the material for Eveningstar. From there Eveningstar can set Banishment if you haven't used it already or Contact + either Enchantment or Sanctified, then Eveningstar effect to copy Banishment effect to add the other trap or a name if you need fodder for the set trap. With Morningstar in grave with Dark Dance, you SHOULD be able to have at least one of the traps alongside a boardwipe off of summoning First Darklord with Morningstar as material.

 

Update + Access is there for when you inevitably get to turn 3 and Rebellion can be swapped for their new trap card, which isn't on YGOpro yet.

 

This deck was kinda just slapped together so it may not be optimal, especially considering the lack of generic fairy endboard pieces. However I think it's a decent show of what Darklords can potentially do now that they actually have a way to access more of their backrow and have enough fodder to activate it.

 

Oh, and they can finally CONSISTENTLY summon First Darklord. Did I mention that? Did I mention that Darklords ONLY NOW have a way to CONSISTENTLY summon The First Darklord, their ONLY boss monster until now? Because the ONLY way to do it previously on the opponent's turn (so that First Darklord ACTUALLY DID SOMETHING outside of it's res.) was through Darklord Uprising, which is a FIVE CARD COMMITTMENT since you not only need to have Uprising and the three material (in hand or on field) for First Darklord, but also A DISCARD. The bonus for using Uprising was gaining up to 2900 LP.

deck_excerpt: It's a small world we live in!
deck_description:
Ascator, Dawnwalker can discard a card to special summon himself from your hand and Fire Ant Ascator from your deck to make level 8 synchros. The best level 8 synchro to summon is Centur-Ion Primera Primus, whose effect can access your Centur-Ion cards.

Planet Pathfinder can search for Stand Up Centur-Ion! to start your Centur-Ion plays, but it's also a Small World bridge that connects Ascator, Dawnwalker to Centur-Ions.

Centur-Ion True Awakening and Mannadium Reframing are this deck's versions of Solemn Judgment. Centur-Ion Primera and Centur-Ion Auxila can search for True Awakening, and Centur-Ion Bonds can help support its cost. Mannadium Reframing can be searched for with Visas Amritara. 

Omega Judgment is this deck's version of Icarus Attack, but Auxila's effect prevents your face-up spells and traps from being destroyed by card effects, essentially making it free destruction.

Lastly, Lunalight Perfume Dancer and Stardust Spark Dragon are for the theoretical Lunalight match-up, but I'm not sure if they're good in practice. Ultimate Slayer can send Perfume Dancer to the graveyard, then you can activate her graveyard effect to drop a Lunalight Liger Dancer's attack to 300, making her easier to destroy by battle with Stardust Spark Dragon. Stardust Spark Dragon's effect can target itself to prevent it from being destroyed by battle or card effect, making it immune to Liger Dancer's quick effect.

Chimera HecaHands is a deck built on intelligent hybridization: the raw power of the Chimera engine collides with the constant pressure of the HecaHands, turning every opening hand into a tangible threat.

 

The game plan is clear and uncompromising: control the tempo, drain the opponent’s resources, and close the game with Fusion monsters that hit like final verdicts. The Chimeras provide presence and resilience, while the HecaHands punish hesitation, breaking boards and momentum with surgical precision.

 

This is not a deck that runs on autopilot. It reads the game, adapts, and strikes exactly when it needs to. Every decision has a cost, every summon carries a consequence. Victory here doesn’t come from inertia, but from vision.

 

A deck for those who embrace disciplined chaos, who understand that true strength isn’t striking first — it’s being the last one standing.

So here's the thing. There was this long combo, all planned out, with a bunch of convoluted Table500-style steps to be consistently bringing out Magia + friends, in a frame that was also able to pivot if need be. And then this guy showed up and slashed the maindeck and extradeck requirements by half and yes I'm still bitter. That being said, the new version has an extremely easy-line to execute (Maiden of White + discard):

• Maiden eff to activate True Light, True Light eff for Wishes for Eyes of Blue.
• Wishes for Sage with Eyes of Blue & Ultimate Fusion, NS Sage eff grab Kaibaman the Legend.
• Link Sage into Spirit with Eyes of Blue, Spirit eff grab Mausoleum of White, additional NS Kaibaman, eff SS the og.
• Wishes GY eff equip Ultimate to the og, SS Tyrant via its own condition, synchro with Kaibaman for Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon.
• Mausoleum eff targeting either to send the og to the GY, Link Spirit eff to revive an og.
• Trigger effects, Maiden to revive herself, Kaibaman to search Chaos MAX.
• (Note: Here's the only tricky part to this, the sequencing require to synchro the Kaibaman away before the Link Spirit eff so he's in the GY to trigger.)
• Synchro Maiden with the og to make a second Spirit, eff tag out both for Ultimate Spirit and Crimson, then eff Crimson to tag into Sifr.
• Activate Ulti fusion, shuffle back Chaos MAX & Ultimate for Magia. 

And now there's space for more non-engine (even in this purposefully less powerful version), and the ED has space for the second link spirit, Khaos, and Mike. Chaos Angel might be a bit of a waste, Lightstorm would be neat, but oh well.
