Thanks you for reading!^_^

VexatioMemoriaAeternumLamentaVenerabilis

Summary:

The story follows two souls who meet in the afterlife after living vastly different lives. One was born into luxury, inheriting wealth and power and eventually controlling one of the world’s most influential companies. The other was born into hardship, never knowing stability or even parental care, surviving by moving from town to town.
Originally, their deaths were meant to reflect this imbalance, but both ultimately die at the hands of police, giving them a shared moment of injustice. One soul was newly married, only to discover her husband’s cruelty—he married her solely to steal her company. There is an implication she may have been pregnant, highlighting the deep and persistent unfairness faced by women. The other soul’s life reflects the quieter injustice endured by men of the common class, marked by neglect and disposability.
In the afterlife, they find themselves in purgatory. One is unable to speak, while the other remains aware and reflective. Together, they attempt to find meaning and comfort in each other’s presence before the cosmos resets, knowing their time is limited.

Work Text:

‚õß Two Souls Too Late ‚õß
By VexatioMemoriaAeternumLamentaVenerabilis, and GPT ^_^ 

 ‚õß Petals at the Edge of Purgatory ‚õß

 

In life, she was known as Beatrice.

 

A quiet girl who noticed the world too deeply and spoke too softly for it to reward her. People mistook her silence for sweetness until they learned what it hid: calculation, patience—something sharp kept clean.

 

She grew up where everything had a price and nothing was ever free—not praise, not loyalty, not love. She learned to trade what the world valued: beauty shaped into a weapon, intellect sharpened into leverage, politeness worn like armor.

 

She rose fast.

She rose alone.

 

And then she married.

 

Champagne. Cameras. A dress that cost more than some people’s houses. A ceremony scripted to look like destiny.

 

But marriage, to men like him, was just a pen.

 

Her husband did not take her name. He took her access. He smiled beside her like a partner, then moved behind her like a thief. He learned her signatures, her schedules, her blind spots. He waited until the company—her company, the inheritance she’d been trained to guard like a kingdom—was close enough to snatch.

 

When she finally understood what he was, the betrayal arrived with the calm of a locked door.

 

Not even rage hurt at first. Not even humiliation.

 

It was the sick realization that she had been handled like an asset.

That even her vows had been paperwork.

 

She drove that night as if speed could undo contracts—

as if the road would bend out of respect for her fury.

 

She never saw the cruiser until it was already there—flashing lights like judgment, like heaven’s cheap imitation of authority.

 

Her last thought was not prayer.

 

It was bitter, sharp, and utterly hers:

Fine. If this is a setback, then what’s the leverage? Where’s the angle? What’s the best move?

 

And then metal screamed—

and the world ended before she could finish turning it into something salvageable.

 

Impact.

 

Darkness.

 

Across the world—far from champagne, far from boardrooms—someone else died under the same cold logic: uniforms, suspicion, a finger on a trigger that did not hesitate long enough to see a person.

 

He had no name in life that anyone kept.

 

Not a name that meant shelter. Not a name that meant family. Not a name spoken with tenderness and repeated until it became belonging.

 

He drifted from town to town the way smoke drifts: visible, unwanted, blamed for the air turning sour. He survived on scraps of work, scraps of warmth, scraps of attention that lasted only as long as someone needed something carried, lifted, fixed.

 

People called him too quiet.

Too strange.

Too much.

 

And women—when they smiled—smiled the way people smile at stray dogs: briefly, kindly, with one hand already reaching for the door.

 

He wanted one thing. One stupid, human thing:

 

To be chosen.

Just once.

To be stayed with—until death did them part.

 

Death arrived first.

 

Not noble. Not cinematic.

 

Just a gun.

A moment.

A breath that didn’t come back.

 

And a thought so small it almost didn’t count:

 

Maybe next life.

 

Time passed.

 

He was used. She was consumed.

He broke slowly. She collapsed all at once.

 

Their endings were quiet enough to be forgotten.

 

But the universe—vast, indifferent, and strangely thorough—noticed the symmetry.

 

So it filed them somewhere else.

 

Not heaven.

Not hell.

The in-between.

 

Purgatory did not feel like fire.

It felt like waiting.

 

A gray plain stretched without horizon, as if distance itself had grown tired. The sky hung low and bruised, threaded with thin fractures of light—like cracks in glass, like the cosmos already preparing to split and pour itself into a new beginning.

 

There were no clocks here.

 

Only the sense of countdown—measured not in hours, but in strain. In the way the sky trembled when the fractures widened. In the way the air sometimes tasted like snow just before it falls.

 

He woke in a crypt half-buried in ash-colored soil.

 

His body was wrong.

 

Too heavy. Too stitched. Too strong in a way that did not feel like power—only like punishment given muscle.

 

When he tried to speak, sound refused him. His throat produced only a low rumble—stone grinding against stone.

 

He sat up, and something stamped itself into him—an identity not chosen, but assigned:

 

Number 22: Zombiestein.

 

Not a name from life.

A title.

A classification.

A card etched into the bones of his new form.

 

He clenched his ruined hands and stared at them as if anger could teach them how to be human again.

 

Behind him, lightning crawled across the clouds—not natural lightning, but something ritual and deliberate. Necromancy dressed as weather.

 

From that light, she rose.

 

Silk clung to her like a memory of luxury—cursed silk, heavier than fabric should be, moving as if it remembered being admired. Her eyes were bright with cold intelligence, her posture intact in a world that wanted everything to slump.

 

She was beautiful the way a rose is beautiful: deliberate, cultivated, and protected by thorns.

People admired her from a distance—then called her cruel the moment they bled.

 

And the universe labeled her with equal indifference:

 

Miss Zombiestein.

 

Beatrice took one step, then another, as if testing whether the afterlife would dare deny her footing.

 

Her heel sank slightly into the ash.

 

She frowned, offended by the texture of eternity.

 

Then she looked up at him.

 

Not with fear.

Not with pity.

 

With appraisal—like a CEO evaluating a new liability.

 

He rose to his full height. The movement felt automatic, an old survival reflex: become larger, become harder to dismiss.

 

He tried to warn her anyway—because some remnants of him still believed women should not be dragged into monsters.

 

A sound like distant thunder strained out of him.

 

She watched his jaw, the tension in his shoulders, the way his hands curled and uncurled as if searching for words.

 

And then—without hesitation—she supplied them.

 

“You’re trying to say,” she said, voice dry as ash, “that I shouldn’t be here. That I shouldn’t look like this.”

 

She tilted her head. Her mouth curved with humor that didn’t quite reach her eyes.

 

“That’s sweet. In a grotesque sort of way.”

 

His eyes narrowed. Rage moved through him like weather.

 

She stepped closer, her silk trailing faint smoke. The air around her smelled of ozone and expensive perfume ruined by grave-dirt.

 

“You’re not wrong,” she said, softer now, as if speaking to herself. “I shouldn’t be here. But you and I don’t get what we should.”

 

He made another sound—low, frustrated.

 

Again she translated, like she’d known him forever.

 

“You’re also thinking,” she went on, “that you don’t deserve this either.”

 

She let out a single quiet laugh. Not mocking. Not kind. Just honest.

 

“I agree. But the universe never asked what we deserved.”

 

Above them, the sky’s fractures pulsed.

 

One of the cracks twitched—and for a moment it didn’t look like light.

 

It looked like a chain.

 

Beatrice followed his gaze. Her expression sharpened.

 

“Of course,” she murmured. “Contracts.”

 

She spoke the word like a curse.

 

Then she looked back at him, and something in her face changed—just a fraction less cruel.

 

“If we’re stuck here,” she said, “then we do it properly.”

 

He stiffened. She watched him, reading the slight angle of his head, the twitch of his fingers—then she smiled like she’d just won an argument he hadn’t realized they were having.

 

“You don’t like that,” she said. “You want to be alone. You’ve always been alone. It’s familiar.”

 

She stepped into his space as if fear had never paid her bills.

 

“Too bad.”

 

He rumbled.

 

She nodded, satisfied. “Yes. Exactly. ‘Too bad.’”

 

Somewhere in the plain, a patch of ghost-flowers trembled into existence—pale petals like moonlight trapped in plant form. They did not grow so much as appear, as if the world occasionally remembered beauty by accident.

 

Beatrice stared at them as if offended that purgatory dared try softness.

 

Then she looked at him again.

 

The stitched giant, voiceless and furious.

A monster with hands big enough to break her.

 

And yet—standing still, as if he didn’t trust himself to move too fast near something fragile.

 

Her expression hardened to cover the sudden ache behind it.

 

“Fine,” she said, brisk. “If we’re waiting for the universe to reset, we wait efficiently.”

 

He blinked.

 

She sighed as if explaining a simple concept to an employee.

 

“You’re carrying me.”

 

His posture went rigid with indignation.

 

She watched the indignation, then supplied his words again, amused.

 

“You’re thinking: ‘Absolutely not.’”

 

She lifted an eyebrow. “And I’m thinking: heels are hell.”

 

He hesitated—only a moment—then crouched.

 

Beatrice climbed onto his back like it was natural, like she had always belonged there.

 

His muscles tightened beneath her weight. He stood carefully, as if she were something breakable.

 

Beatrice glanced at the side of his face, at the stitched line of his jaw, and her voice softened without permission.

 

“You’re gentler than you look,” she said.

 

He made a sound—half rumble, half complaint.

 

She smirked. “Yes, yes. Don’t ruin your image.”

 

They walked through gray forever together.

 

And in that forever—something strange happened.

 

The waiting started to feel less like punishment.

 

Because for the first time in either of their lives, neither of them was rushing toward an ending alone.

 

The sky still cracked. The cosmos still counted down toward its reset.

 

But when the fractures widened, Beatrice didn’t look up with fear.

 

She looked at him, as if daring the universe to interrupt.

 

Days—or what passed for days—collected like dust.

 

Sometimes the plain stayed barren.

Sometimes it bloomed with ghost-flowers.

 

And then, one quiet stretch of gray, he stopped walking.

 

Beatrice shifted on his back, irritated. “What now—”

 

He set her down carefully, like placing something valuable on a shelf.

 

He walked toward a single flower standing apart from the others—pale, stubborn, impossible.

 

His large stitched hand hovered above it, trembling with a restraint that didn’t match the violence of his form.

 

He plucked it.

 

The fragile bloom looked absurd in his ruined fingers.

 

He turned back to her.

 

For a moment, Beatrice forgot how to smirk.

 

His eyes—hollow, shadowed—held something that did not belong in purgatory.

 

Hope.

 

He extended the flower toward her.

 

A gift without a contract.

A gesture without a price.

 

Beatrice stared at it as if it might explode.

 

“…You’ve never given a woman a flower,” she said, and it wasn’t quite a question.

 

He shook his head once.

 

Her throat tightened. She covered it with sarcasm the way she covered everything.

 

“It’s a little late for romance,” she murmured.

 

But she reached out anyway—

 

—and the sky tore open.

 

No warning.

No mercy.

 

Chains of summoning magic ripped through the plain like claws through cloth. The air screamed. The fractures in the sky widened into a jagged doorway, and the chain found him the way a hook finds flesh.

 

His body jerked upward.

 

The flower stayed clenched in his hand.

 

A tear—hot, humiliating, human—slid down his cheek as he was dragged away mid-gift, mid-moment, mid-almost.

 

Not again, his body said, even if his mouth could not.

Not now.

 

Beatrice’s eyes widened.

 

Not because she was afraid of the magic—

 

but because she recognized it.

 

The same kind of force that had ruled her entire life: authority without intimacy. Power without care.

 

“Of course,” she hissed. “Of course they’d interrupt this.”

 

He vanished through the rift—

 

—and reappeared on a battlefield of the living.

 

A duel in progress.

 

The world here had color: harsh lights, roaring crowds, digital storms. Voices shouted rules like prayers.

 

“I Special Summon Number 22: Zombiestein!”

 

He hit the field in Attack Position, still holding the flower like an accusation.

 

Across from him, a monster rose—something smug and over-designed, radiating the kind of confidence only the living could afford.

 

The duelist’s command snapped again:

 

“Activate effect—switch it to Defense Position!”

 

Magic seized his limbs. Forced him down. Locked him into helplessness.

 

The flower bent in his fist. His rage surged.

 

For one violent second he almost threw it—almost hurled that delicate thing like a weapon at the monster responsible.

 

But he didn’t.

 

He couldn’t.

 

He held it tighter, as if refusing to let the universe take everything—

even this.

 

And then—

 

a second chain flickered into being, crossing the rift like a leash made of moonlight.

 

Beatrice stepped through.

 

Not as a summoned monster.

 

As a consequence.

 

Her cursed silk trailed smoke. Her eyes glowed with necromantic lightning. And in her hand, she held the chain attached to him—not yanking, not controlling, but claiming.

 

She slid behind him, close enough that her presence pressed into his back like warmth.

 

To the duelists, she was invisible—an afterlife glitch the living weren’t meant to see.

 

To him, she was everything.

 

Her voice cut through the battlefield, low and viciously intimate:

 

“Idiot.”

 

He shuddered.

 

“You don’t give flowers to strangers,” she whispered, her breath like cold electricity. “You were giving it to me.”

 

Her fingers tightened on the chain.

 

Her voice sharpened with satisfaction—almost playful, almost dangerous.

 

“That flower is mine.”

 

His shoulders shook with silent fury.

 

Beatrice watched the way his fingers protected the crushed bloom even while magic tried to humiliate him.

 

And she translated him again, fond and sharp at once:

 

“You’re thinking: ‘I tried. I tried to do it right.’”

 

Her grip tightened on the chain.

 

“So did I,” she murmured. “In my own way.”

 

She lifted her hand.

 

The chain flared.

 

In the space where a card effect would resolve, something else resolved instead:

 

A bond.

An equip.

A rule written by two dead people who had finally decided to stop being polite to fate.

 

Beatrice’s presence snapped the humiliation like a thread.

 

Defense broke.

 

Attack Position surged back—not because the duelist commanded it, but because she refused to let him be powerless again.

 

His roar shook the field.

 

The duelists shouted, confused, as if the game had briefly developed a soul.

 

Beatrice leaned in, lips near his ear, and spoke the words he could not:

 

“Now.”

 

Together, they moved.

 

(Here you can plug in your true Yu-Gi-Oh sequence later—chain links, negates, battle step, token usage. The emotional engine is set: her bond restores his agency.)

 

When the last opposing monster shattered into light, the battlefield dimmed. The crowd noise blurred. The duel ended. The living realm dissolved like a dream the dead were never meant to share.

 

And Zombiestein stood there, still clutching the flower—now bruised, bent, but not gone.

 

Beatrice reached out and took it gently, as if her hands remembered softness only in private.

 

Her voice, when she spoke, was smaller than usual.

 

“…It’s about time someone gave me one.”

 

They stepped back through the rift into purgatory.

 

The gray plain returned.

 

The sky’s fractures pulsed overhead—counting down to the reset, to the ending that was really a beginning.

 

Beatrice looked up at the cracks, then down at him.

 

In her eyes was something close to anger, but not at him.

 

At the waste.

At the rush.

At the lives they’d spent sprinting toward survival, never stopping long enough to realize what they were actually running toward.

 

“You know what’s funny?” she said softly.

 

He tilted his head.

 

Her mouth twitched into something that almost counted as a smile. “We spent our whole lives acting like we had time.”

 

Zombiestein’s fingers flexed.

 

Beatrice watched the motion, then spoke for him, voice gentler than her words:

 

“You’re thinking: ‘I didn’t. I always knew time was a lie.’”

 

She nodded slowly, accepting it.

 

Then she stepped closer and rested her head against his chest—against stitches and thunder and the impossible steadiness of him.

 

“Then let’s not waste what we have now,” she whispered. “Before the universe starts pretending again.”

 

Above them, the sky cracked wider.

 

Somewhere beyond the fractures, stars were already folding themselves into new shapes—resetting, restarting, rewriting.

 

And in the gray waiting place between endings, two dead souls did something neither had been allowed to do in life:

 

They stopped rushing.

 

They held each other like time could be convinced to hesitate.

 

And for a while—

 

it did.

 

‚õß The Petals Before the Crack ‚õß

 

The first time Beatrice noticed the Flower Tokens, she hated them.

 

Not because they were ugly—purgatory’s flowers were never ugly, only pale and wrong, like moonlight trying to imitate skin. She hated them because they were accounting.

 

One morning the gray plain woke up with four blossoms arranged neatly around them, each petal shaped like a small, stubborn refusal. They didn’t grow from soil. They appeared in the air beside her silk and settled into invisible slots like paperwork finding its folder.

 

Beatrice stared at them for a long time.

 

Zombiestein watched her watching them. His head tilted. His hand lifted as if he wanted to touch one—but hesitated, afraid his fingers would crush the concept of fragile time.

 

She exhaled through her nose. “Don’t look so proud. This isn’t a gift.”

 

His chest rumbled softly.

 

Beatrice’s eyes narrowed. She pointed at the flowers as if accusing them. “You’re thinking: Oh. Four. Like that means something.”

 

He didn’t deny it. He couldn’t. His shoulders rose a fraction—the closest he came to a shrug.

 

Beatrice folded her arms. “Fine. Yes. Four.”

 

She leaned closer to the petals. Their edges shimmered, as if the universe had cut them from the same material as the sky’s cracks.

 

“They’re minutes,” she decided. “Not real minutes. Purgatory minutes.”

 

His hand hovered again.

 

Beatrice slapped his wrist lightly—not hard enough to hurt, just enough to feel like ownership. “Careful. If you break one, I’m billing you.”

 

His rumble shifted—almost offended.

 

She smiled despite herself. “Yes. Exactly. How do you bill someone when you’re dead? Welcome to my world.”

 

From then on, the Flower Tokens became their private joke.

 

When he carried her for too long and his steps started to drag, she’d tap his shoulder twice—her signal.

 

He would pause.

 

She’d glance at the petals and say, with manufactured boredom, “We can’t afford to be sentimental today.”

 

He would rumble again—low, displeased.

 

And she would translate him, because she always did.

 

“You’re thinking: I can carry you.”

 

“I know,” she’d say, voice softer than her words. “That’s the problem.”

 

And sometimes—only sometimes—she would lift a hand and let one petal dissolve into glittering ash.

 

The world would ease, just a little.

The sky would hesitate.

And his spine would straighten as if the universe had loosened its grip on him for the price of a single flower.

 

Borrowed time.

 

Paid in petals.

 

They learned other things too—small, domestic rituals made from nothing.

 

Beatrice discovered that purgatory had lost property.

 

Not a building. Not a clerk. Just… places where discarded objects collected as if the afterlife couldn’t bear to waste what the living abandoned.

 

They found them in pockets of fog: a cracked Duel Disk faceplate, a single die with the corners worn smooth, half a deck box stamped with someone’s initials, a broken chain link that looked too real to be metaphor.

 

Beatrice held up the deck box lid and squinted. “Someone out there misses this.”

 

Zombiestein leaned down, close enough that his breath stirred her hair.

 

She glanced at him and smirked. “Don’t get ideas. We are not starting a hobby.”

 

His fingers tapped once against his thigh—impatient.

 

Beatrice sighed theatrically. “Yes, yes. You’re thinking: It already is a hobby.”

 

They began collecting strange relics anyway—because waiting demanded something to do besides ache.

 

Beatrice arranged the objects in neat rows. Zombiestein would bring her new ones without being asked, placing them at her feet like offerings: a torn card sleeve, a dented coin, a tiny charm shaped like a star.

 

The first time he found a ring, he stared at it for a long time before handing it to her.

 

Beatrice didn’t comment. Not immediately.

 

Then she slid it onto one finger—where it didn’t fit—and said lightly, “There. Now I’m married to the afterlife. Again. Thrilling.”

 

Zombiestein’s rumble came out rougher than usual, like laughter that didn’t know how to be laughter.

 

Beatrice’s smirk softened. “That’s the closest thing to a laugh I’ve ever heard from you.”

 

He looked away, as if embarrassed by the sound.

 

She watched him and spoke for him, voice gentler: “You’re thinking: I don’t know how.”

 

“I know,” she said. “Neither did I.”

 

Sometimes other monsters wandered through their purgatory like misplaced cards: creatures whose forms belonged to wars and arenas and childhood bedrooms.

 

Some were violent, drawn to Zombiestein’s stitched power the way predators test fences.

Some were simply… lost, looking for the field they’d been summoned to and never finding it.

 

A small winged thing—more shadow than body—circled them one day, chittering.

 

Beatrice tilted her head. “Is that… trying to duel us?”

 

Zombiestein lifted his hand. The creature flinched.

 

Beatrice clicked her tongue. “Don’t. You’ll scare it.”

 

He froze, obedient in a way that still surprised her.

 

She crouched—careful with her heels—and picked up one of the ghostly flowers from the ground, holding it out. The creature drifted closer, sniffed the air as if flowers were language, then took the petal delicately.

 

Beatrice smiled. “There. See? Diplomacy.”

 

Zombiestein rumbled—skeptical.

 

Beatrice translated without looking at him: “You’re thinking: If it bites you, I’m biting it back.”

 

She straightened. “Obviously.”

 

Another day they met something larger—a hulking figure made of armor-plates and old wrath, dragging a rusted weapon behind it. It paused when it saw Zombiestein, posture turning territorial.

 

Zombiestein’s shoulders squared. He stepped forward.

 

Beatrice touched the chain in her hand—more instinct than spell—and the Flower Tokens shivered.

 

The armored monster’s gaze flicked to Beatrice, then to the chain, then to the petals.

 

It understood something.

 

It backed away.

 

Beatrice watched it go and muttered, “Even in death, men respect paperwork.”

 

Zombiestein rumbled—a sound like agreement.

 

She smiled. “Yes. Exactly.”

 

They learned each other’s patterns so well it became its own language.

 

When Zombiestein was angry, his right hand would clench twice.

When he was afraid—rare, but real—his fingers would go still, as if motion would make the universe notice him.

When he was gentle, he moved like a cathedral: slow, careful, built to hold something sacred.

 

Beatrice pretended she didn’t notice any of it.

 

But she did.

 

And in return, he learned her too—her false laughter versus her real silence, the way her sarcasm sharpened when she was close to crying, the way she stared at the sky’s cracks longer on days she didn’t want to admit she was counting.

 

One evening—if “evening” meant anything in a place without sun—Beatrice rested against his chest and said, quiet enough to be honest:

 

“I think we were rushing.”

 

Zombiestein didn’t move.

 

Beatrice translated him anyway, because she could feel the question in the stillness: “Rushing toward what?”

 

She swallowed. “Toward the end. Toward the next thing. Toward being finished.”

 

She pressed her palm over one of his stitches, like she could seal the past shut. “I spent my life trying to outrun loneliness by winning.”

 

His head dipped slightly.

 

Beatrice’s voice softened. “And you spent your life trying to outrun loneliness by surviving.”

 

He rumbled—low, pained.

 

“You’re thinking: It didn’t work,” she said.

 

“It didn’t,” she agreed. “Not until now.”

 

They were happy, in the way two ruined things can be happy: not bright, not perfect, but real.

 

And purgatory—out of either boredom or cruelty—let it last long enough that it started to feel dangerous.

 

Then the summoning came again.

 

The sky didn’t tear this time. It split.

 

A crack opened from horizon to horizon like a mouth deciding to speak. Chains dropped through it in slow, inevitable arcs, seeking their assigned target.

 

Zombiestein stiffened.

 

Beatrice’s fingers tightened around the chain she held—their chain, the one that felt less like control and more like proof.

 

“No,” she said immediately.

 

Zombiestein’s jaw clenched. His body leaned toward the crack—rage and obedience fighting in him the way they always had.

 

Beatrice watched his posture and spoke for him with a tenderness so sharp it almost hurt.

 

“You’re thinking: If I go, you’ll be alone.”

 

Her throat tightened. “Yes.”

 

Another chain snaked down.

 

Zombiestein’s feet began to lift.

 

Beatrice lifted her hand—fast, decisive—and burned a Flower Token.

 

A petal dissolved into ash.

 

The pull hesitated.

 

The universe stalled—as if surprised anyone would dare pay a cost to argue with it.

 

Zombiestein’s feet touched the ground again.

 

Beatrice exhaled, trembling with anger. “There. I bought us a second.”

 

Zombiestein turned his head toward her, eyes hollow and bright.

 

She swallowed and translated what he couldn’t say: “You’re thinking: Don’t spend them all.”

 

She smiled, small and tired. “I wasn’t planning on it.”

 

The crack above them widened anyway.

 

Not a summoning tear this time.

 

A structural failure.

 

The sky itself looked… stressed, like cloth pulled too thin.

 

Beatrice stared upward. “That’s not a duel.”

 

Zombiestein’s hands curled slowly.

 

Beatrice’s voice went careful. “That’s the reset.”

 

They had known it was coming the way people know winter comes—abstractly, until the first frost touches skin.

 

Now it was here, and the sky didn’t pretend otherwise.

 

The fractures spread. Light leaked through, not warm or holy—just raw and unfinished, like the universe behind the universe.

 

The objects they’d collected—the lost Duel Disk piece, the coin, the ring—began to tremble where they lay, as if remembering they didn’t belong to this cycle.

 

Beatrice watched them and felt something inside her shift.

 

Memories—hers, his—began to loosen at the edges.

 

Not vanishing yet.

 

Packing.

 

Like a house being boxed up before eviction.

 

She pressed a hand to her temple. Images flickered: champagne, cameras, a locked door; snow on concrete; a gun’s bark; an empty stomach; a wedding dress; a shelter intake form.

 

Zombiestein swayed, one hand braced against the air as if he could hold himself together by force.

 

Beatrice stepped into him and grabbed his wrist.

 

He looked down at her.

 

She had translated him for so long that now she didn’t wait for the body language.

 

She spoke first.

 

“Listen,” she said.

 

Zombiestein’s shoulders tightened. He tried to speak. Only thunder came.

 

Beatrice shook her head. “No. Don’t waste effort on a mouth you don’t have. I’ll do it.”

 

The Flower Tokens flared softly at her shoulder.

 

Two petals left.

 

Two hesitations.

 

Two small bribes offered to a collapsing cosmos.

 

Beatrice stared at them, then at him, and something in her expression finally surrendered—pride, control, the habit of pretending she didn’t need anyone.

 

“I don’t know what we’ll be,” she said, voice breaking around the words. “When this starts again.”

 

Zombiestein’s fingers curled around her hand—gentle, huge, careful.

 

Beatrice nodded as if answering him. “Yes. I know. You’re thinking: We won’t remember.”

 

Her laugh came out small and ugly. “Of course we won’t. That would be too kind.”

 

The sky cracked wider.

 

A wave of pressure rolled over the plain. The ghost-flowers bent as if in wind.

 

The relics they’d collected lifted into the air and began drifting upward, dissolving into specks of light—returned to wherever the universe stored its forgotten things.

 

Beatrice watched the ring vanish last.

 

Her jaw clenched.

 

Then she looked up at him with that old, weaponized composure trying to return—and failing.

 

“Promise me something,” she said.

 

Zombiestein’s head tilted.

 

She didn’t translate this time. She didn’t make it a joke.

 

“Promise me you’ll find me,” she whispered. “Even if you don’t know my name. Even if you don’t know yours.”

 

His chest rumbled—a broken, desperate sound.

 

Beatrice nodded, tears gathering despite her. “Yes. That. That’s a promise.”

 

The remaining Flower Tokens shivered, as if offended to be emotional.

 

Beatrice lifted her hand and touched one petal with her fingertip.

 

“Last purchase,” she murmured.

 

She burned it.

 

The petal dissolved, and for a heartbeat the reset slowed—just enough for her to press her forehead against his chest, just enough for him to fold his arms around her without crushing her, just enough to feel like the universe could be made to wait if they asked correctly.

 

Beatrice spoke into his stitches, into his thunder, into the place where a heartbeat would have been.

 

“When it starts again,” she said, “I don’t want another life where we rush toward suffering just because we think that’s what living is.”

 

Zombiestein held her tighter—not hard, just certain—like he was trying to memorize her shape with his bones.

 

Beatrice’s voice shook. “I want us to be happy sooner.”

 

His hand lifted—awkward, trembling.

 

And from somewhere—no longer the ground, no longer the air—a single ghost-flower appeared in his fingers again, as if the universe, for one last cruel joke, remembered what it had interrupted.

 

He offered it to her.

 

Beatrice laughed through tears. “You’re doing this now?”

 

He couldn’t answer.

 

So he did what he always did: held it out, steady as thunder trying to be gentle.

 

Beatrice took it, and her fingers closed around his.

 

“Mine,” she whispered—soft this time, not possessive, just afraid. “You’re mine.”

 

The sky opened fully.

 

Not tearing.

 

Unfolding.

 

Light poured down like the first page of a new book.

 

Beatrice felt her thoughts begin to slip—the sharpness softening, the names loosening, the edges of her life turning blank.

 

Zombiestein swayed, his title trembling inside him like a word about to be erased.

 

Beatrice clutched his hand harder. “Don’t let go.”

 

His fingers tightened.

 

He rumbled—one last sound that carried everything he couldn’t say.

 

Beatrice closed her eyes and translated it anyway, because she couldn’t stop herself, because this was how she loved:

 

“You’re thinking: I will find you. Even if I have to die a thousand times to do it.”

 

Her breath hitched. “Good.”

 

The flower in her hand began to dissolve.

 

The chain in her grip turned to light.

 

The plain faded.

 

And as the universe reset—stars folding, rules rewriting, everything pretending it had never broken—two souls went with it, not as monsters, not as titles, not as class and gender and tragedy…

 

…but as something stubborn.

 

A promise.

 

Something the cosmos would have to work to erase completely.

 

Because even as their memories packed themselves into darkness, even as names emptied out, even as the new world inhaled—

 

Beatrice’s last thought—small, fierce, and utterly hers—was not leverage.

 

It was not strategy.

 

It was simple, finally honest, and not salvageable into anything else:

 

Find me.

 

And somewhere in the blank space where Zombiestein’s voice should have been, his answer remained—not in words, but in the shape of his hands remembering how to hold her.

Title: Petals at the Edge of Purgatory

Fandom: Yu-Gi-Oh!
Rating: Teen
Archive Warnings: Major Character Death, Social Inequality
Categories: Gen, F/F undertones, Philosophical, M/F
Additional Tags: Afterlife, Purgatory, Class Divide, Gender Inequality, Corporate Corruption, Soul Bonds, Original Card Lore, Tragedy, Quiet Intimacy, Cosmic Reset

Summary

Two souls arrive in the afterlife under the same cold authority of flashing lights and drawn guns.

In life, they never should have met.

One was born into wealth—an heiress groomed to inherit one of the world’s most powerful corporations. Her marriage, celebrated by cameras and champagne, concealed a calculated betrayal: a husband who wed her not for love, but for control. Her death came swiftly, violently, and unjustly—another woman erased by ambition not her own.

The other had no such legacy. No inheritance. No stability. Raised between towns and temporary shelters, his life was a series of compromises made simply to survive. He never owned much—except his convictions. His death, too, came at the hands of a system that offered suspicion before mercy.

Now, in purgatory, their paths finally cross.

She cannot speak.
He cannot stop listening.

As the cosmos itself prepares for a reset, the two souls share borrowed time—moments of fragile peace amid endless waiting. Together, they begin to understand the quiet cruelties of the world they left behind: how power protects some, how silence devours others, and how unfairness wears different faces depending on who you are.

From this union of grief and understanding, something new stirs—an echo within the cards themselves.

Author’s Notes

This story began as an experiment: What happens when Yu-Gi-Oh! cards are treated not as mechanics first, but as memories?

The original concept involved random accidents—trucks, chance, inevitability—but I ultimately chose police violence so both characters would share a single, systemic thread. Their deaths are not coincidence; they are consequence.

This is a story about imbalance:

  • The cost of being a woman in a world that commodifies marriage

  • The cost of being a man without capital in a society that equates worth with ownership

  • And how neither wealth nor morality guarantees safety

Their time in purgatory is intentionally quiet. This is not a battle story—it is a waiting story.

Original Card Concept (Story Integration)

Miss Zombiestein
DARK | Zombie | Effect

Born from grief rather than decay, Miss Zombiestein is not discarded—she is remembered.

  • May be equipped to Zombiestein

  • Upon equip, place up to four Flower Tokens in the Spell & Trap Zones

  • Instead of discarding cards to activate Zombiestein’s effect, remove Flower Tokens

  • Zombiestein’s effect scales with the number of Flower Tokens removed

  • Zombiestein can never be switched to Defense Position while this card is equipped

The flowers represent borrowed time—each petal a moment the universe hesitates before erasing them both.

 

 

Possible Addition / Expansion Scene

(to weave into the “afterdeath” part of your story)

The purgatory stretched on as endless gray plains. Sometimes barren, sometimes blooming in strange patches of ghost-flowers. She never walked if she didn’t have to—because why bother? Death was forever, and heels were hell.

So, he carried her.
Always.

At first, he hated it—grunting under her weight, glaring when she smirked. But she never asked, never apologized. She just leaned against his chest like she owned him.

“Funny,” she’d whisper with that sharp half-smile, “in life, no man could carry me. In death, I’ve found one who has no choice.”

He’d only grunt.
But sometimes, the grunt was softer—almost like a sigh.

One day, among the plains, they stumbled across a patch of flowers, pale as moonlight. He bent down—this huge, stitched-together monster bending like a child—and plucked one.

For a moment, she thought he might crush it in those ruined hands. But instead, awkwardly, he held it out to her.

Her breath caught. She stared.

“…You’ve never given a woman a flower before, have you?”

He shook his head.

“Well,” she said, her voice softening just slightly, “it’s a little late for romance, don’t you think?”

But she took it anyway. And for the first time, she didn’t smirk.

A Darkly Comic Twist

Of course, eternity wasn’t just wandering fields. Sometimes the veil between worlds split, and duels from the living realm echoed through their purgatory. Summoned monsters would rise around them, clashing in fire and thunder.

Every time, he raged. Raged at the chains. At the reminder of battles fought without meaning. And every time, she had to drag him back from the frenzy.

“You’re embarrassing us,” she’d snap, crossing her arms as some fiery demon towered over them.

“Rrragh!” he’d roar back, tearing toward it.

And then, almost lazily, she’d snap her fingers. A twist of ghost-light, a bite of her smirk—and the monster would stagger, its strength undone.

“Honestly,” she’d sigh, “do you ever get tired of losing your temper?”

He’d glance at her, then at the fading monster. Grunt.

She’d roll her eyes. “Yes, yes, I know. Rage eternal, blah blah. Still… I suppose it’s nice knowing you’d break the universe just to avoid leaving me behind.”

For once, he didn’t grunt. He just kept carrying her.

In life, she was known as Beatrice—a quiet girl who noticed the world too deeply and spoke too softly for it to hear her. She used her beauty, her wit, her precision—to gain what she needed from others. She was successful, even envied, but she could never truly connect with people on a personal level. Especially not with those who reminded her of herself—wounded, driven, furious. She resented them. They chased the same goals she did… and she didn’t want to see herself in them.

 

Unlike him.

 

He had no name in life—only one on the grave. He never had enough. Not for food. Not for shelter. He wore rags, wandered from town to town, chasing scraps of meaning. He was tall and silent, slowly eroded by years of harsh winters and lonelier nights.

 

People called him “too quiet,” “too strange,” “too much.” And yet, women smiled at him—only when they needed something. Then disappeared when someone shinier, easier came along.

His chest held hope like cracked vases: fragile, half-full, not all there  (always leaking).

He longed for someone—just one—to choose him, to stay with him… until death due to apart (sadly this moment a female happiest dream) .

 

And then… came death.

 

Not noble. Not cinematic. Just a gun. A moment. A whisper:

“Maybe next life…”

 

Somewhere else, on the other side of the world, Beatrice met her own ending.

Consumed by fury—losing her company to a fancier marriage, someone richer, more ‘desirable’, cunning enough to marry and leave for a new company—she drove fast, blinded by rage. She didn’t see the cruiser. Not until it was too late.

 

Her final thought was bitter irony—wondering if she could’ve used even a police officer to get her power back.

 

Everything she did in life had been for herself.

And now… there was nothing left to take.

 

Time passed.

 

He hurt.

She passed.

He was used.

She was consumed.

He broke slowly.

She collapsed in rage.

And then… they were both gone.

 

No one noticed. No one mourned.

Their deaths were small, quiet, and meaningless to the world.

 

But maybe the universe noticed.

And in that sacred in-between—between breath and bone, between silence and sky—they were given another chance.

He didn't answer. He didn't need to.

 

Because in the afterdeath…

They were no longer too late.

 

There were no clocks here. No endings. Just moments.

 

Moments where she touched his trembling hand.

Moments where he learned to speak again—not with words, but with presence.

Moments where the chain between them—once feared—became sacred.

But now,

He did so with her beside him.

Not above.

Beside.

 

Because love doesn’t always come in life.

 

Sometimes it finds you after the end.

When there’s nothing left to pretend.

Only scars. Only silence.

Only us.

Mark, what you’ve sketched here is fantastic raw ore—a mythic, tragic romance laced with irony, sorrow, and (what you’re leaning toward now) humor. What you’ve got is essentially a gothic love story in a purgatorial sitcom frame: two people who never figured life out, now condemned to spend eternity side-by-side, where the tragic beauty is laced with absurd moments of undead domesticity.

Let me build on your vision while keeping the tone balanced between hauntingly poetic and slyly funny—something that lets Beatrice’s wit clash with his grunt-heavy stoicism, yet never loses that undertone of melancholy.

 











He bent low, massive knees creaking, and plucked the lone flower from the barren field. It looked absurd in his scarred, trembling hand—a fragile thing that should never have survived here, yet did.

He turned toward her, awkward, his silence heavier than any speech. For just a heartbeat, she saw something impossible in his hollow eyes: hope.

But before the flower could touch her palm—

The ground split.
The air screamed.
Chains of summoning magic clawed through the purgatory.

In an instant, he was gone—dragged upward into the battlefield of the living, a pawn in a duel not his own. The flower remained in his hand, the impossible gift, the unspoken word, clutched tight.

Rage boiled through him. The duelists’ voices thundered commands, and he roared, swinging blindly. The flower, absurd in his fist, bent under his grip. In his frenzy, he thrust it forward toward the enemy—like an insult, a token of defiance. As though the fragile bloom could wound what steel and claws could not.

The opponent sneered. The audience laughed. The summoning spell had bound him in defense, shackled and useless.

For a moment, she stood still, furious. How dare the universe tear him away—again—at the very moment he was about to give her something real?

Through the rift, following the chain she had created for him, she arrived. Her cursed silk trailed like smoke, her eyes alight with lightning. Her hands gripped the chains that bound him, daring the spell itself to try and sever them.

She stepped onto the battlefield behind him, voice sharp enough to cut the air:
“Idiot. You don’t hand flowers to strangers. You’re mine, and so is that.”

Her laughter cracked like glass, wild and mocking, as she slid against his back. To the duelists, she was unseen—but to him, he felt her there. Her presence pressed into him, chains lacing through his bones.

The chains snapped him upright. Defense broke. Attack Mode re-engaged. He roared. Together, they raged forward, smashing the opponent’s monsters, while she clung to his back like an unseen weapon. Her laughter—sharp, mocking, electric—curled through every blow, weaving chaos and precision in perfect harmony, giving him the strength to stay in attack mode.

The battlefield erupted around them, but he didn’t notice the world. Only her. Only the way her presence guided him, tethered him, while still letting him be the storm.

When the last monster fell and silence returned, he turned, still trembling, still holding the crushed flower. She reached for it. Her eyes softened ever so slightly as she took it.

“…Well,” she murmured, voice catching, “I suppose it’s about time someone gave me one.”

As they stepped back into purgatory, she led the way, chains in hand, guiding him home.

 

After the duel ended, the battlefield dissolved behind them. Silence returned, the scorched ground and shattered monsters vanishing like smoke. He still held the crushed flower, she still had a hint of lightning in her eyes—but eternity wasn’t just wandering empty fields, silent and gray.

Sometimes the veil between worlds split, and duels from the living realm echoed through their purgatory. Summoned monsters would rise around them, clashing in fire and thunder.

Every time, he raged. Raged at the chains. At the reminder of battles fought without meaning. And every time, she had to drag him back from the frenzy.

“You’re embarrassing us,” she’d snap, crossing her arms as some fiery demon towered over them.

“Rrragh!” he’d roar back, tearing toward it.

And then, almost lazily, she’d snap her fingers. A twist of ghost-light, a bite of her smirk—and the monster would stagger, its strength undone.

“Honestly,” she’d sigh, “do you ever get tired of losing your temper?”

He’d glance at her, then at the fading monster. Grunt.

She rolled her eyes. “Yes, yes, I know. Rage eternal, blah blah. Still… I suppose it’s nice knowing you’d break the universe just to avoid leaving me behind.”

He shook his head.

deck_excerpt: Branded Dracotail for post Burst Protocol
deck_description:
With Burst Protocol approaching at the start of February I felt it was time to update my Dracotail list.  The Branded engine has become standard in TCG since we have multiple Branded Fusion and to enable a 1 card combo in the deck and no Spenta or Invoked Omega to enable the full power Magistus Engine.  Fusing Phyrixul and Albaz or now Fallen of White Dragon makes albion, letting Phyrixul set Ketu to search Lukias who searches Faimena.  This lets you fuse Albion and Lukias into Secreterion setting Rahu, then use Secreterion to bottom Albaz to revive Phyrixul who revives and bounces Faimena. Rahu fuses Faimena and Urgula from deck to make Gulamel setting Horn and Flame, and finally use Urgula to bottom itself and add Faimena back to hand and Albion to set Fallen and the Virtuous in the End Phase.

Fallen of White Dragon is a 1 card combo to make Eccelsia of the Black Dragon who can summon Cartesia from deck for more quick effect Fusions.  Otherwise its pretty similar to the current builds, its just another layer of utility, and since Fallen can summon Ecclesia from grave she can start this combo going second or if you don't need your Normal for Lukias or Mululu.

deck_name: Luis D. Luffy Fiendsmith Goblin Biker Advanced
deck_description:
üèçÔ∏è Goblin Biker / Fiendsmith – Control agresivo con presión constante

Este deck es una mezcla híbrida entre Goblin Biker y Fiendsmith, apoyada por Speedroid para extender jugadas, Bystials para control del cementerio y una cantidad alta de hand traps para frenar al oponente desde turno 1. El resultado es un mazo muy interactivo, capaz de romper campos y luego cerrar partidas rápido.

üîß Motor Goblin Biker – Presión y ventaja incremental

El núcleo del deck gira en torno a Goblin Biker Gone Wild, Dugg Charger y las spells “Grand”:

  • Goblin Biker Grand Entrance / Breakout permiten extender jugadas, reciclar recursos y mantener presencia en campo.

  • Big Gabonga es la principal Xyz del arquetipo, generando presión constante y obligando al rival a gastar recursos.

  • Goblin’s Crazy Beast y D/D/D Wave High King Caesar funcionan como piezas de control y negación.

  • Los Goblin Biker destacan por su capacidad de grind game, ya que pueden seguir produciendo amenazas incluso después de ser interrumpidos.

üëâ El plan es poner cuerpos rápido, forzar respuestas y castigar cualquier error del rival.

üî• Motor Fiendsmith – Ventaja, castigo y cierre

Fiendsmith aporta consistencia y poder de castigo:

  • Fiendsmith Engraver + Lacrima habilitan jugadas hacia Desirae, Requiem y Sequence, creando líneas flexibles según el matchup.

  • Fiendsmith in Paradise agrega control adicional y presión en mid/late game.

  • Agnumday y A Bao A Qu sirven como amenazas difíciles de responder, ideales para cerrar partidas.

Este motor permite al deck convertir pequeñas ventajas en victorias, algo clave en duelos largos.

üå™Ô∏è Speedroid – Extensor explosivo

  • Speedroid Terrortop + Taketomborg es un paquete clásico para iniciar jugadas sin Normal Summon.

  • Facilita acceso a Xyz/Synchro clave como Chaos Angel, que aporta protección y presencia dominante.

‚òÑÔ∏è Hand Traps y control del rival

El deck va cargado de interrupciones:

  • Ash Blossom, Droll & Lock Bird, Mulcharmy Fuwalos ralentizan motores modernos.

  • Nibiru castiga extensiones excesivas.

  • Bystial Magnamhut / Baldrake controlan cementerios Light/Dark y sirven como cuerpos grandes.

  • Infinite Impermanence y Called by the Grave protegen tus jugadas y frenan al oponente.

Esto hace que el deck sea muy fuerte yendo segundo, pero también sólido al empezar.

üåå Extra Deck – Respuestas para todo

El Extra está diseñado para adaptarse a cualquier estado de la partida:

  • S:P Little Knight + I:P Masquerena para interacción en turno del rival.

  • Underworld Goddess para limpiar amenazas imposibles.

  • Chaos Angel como carta de presión y protección.

  • Las Xyz Goblin y Fiendsmith aseguran presencia constante y control del ritmo.

üéØ Condición de victoria

El deck gana al:

  1. Interrumpir fuerte los primeros turnos del rival.

  2. Establecer presión constante con Goblin Biker y Fiendsmith.

  3. Cerrar partidas con jefes del Extra Deck cuando el rival ya no tiene recursos.

‚öñÔ∏è Fortalezas y debilidades

Fortalezas

  • Mucha interacción.

  • Excelente grind game.

  • Flexible y adaptable al meta.

  • Fuerte yendo primero o segundo.

Debilidades

  • Líneas complejas (requiere buen pilotaje).

  • Dependencia del Extra Deck.

  • Puede sufrir contra floodgates pesados si no roba removal.

üß† Conclusión

 

Este es un deck moderno, técnico y agresivo, ideal para jugadores que disfrutan pensar cada jugada, castigar errores y dominar el ritmo del duelo. No gana de un solo combo, sino asfixiando poco a poco al oponente, como debe hacerlo un verdadero Goblin Biker üòàüèçÔ∏è

deck_excerpt: The Man enters an unlikely alliance... With the Fiendsmiths!
deck_description:
First it was Ishizu responsible for creating the strongest Yugioh deck of all time, Ishizu Tearlament... Now is it Odion's turn to dominate competition like he did in Battle City? 

The Man With the Mark - Odion, has certainly "hit the mark" in the competitive Masterduel scene! The latest Masterduel Selection Pack "Aerial Superiority" has been a massive boon for this seemingly forgotten Ishtar sibling, granting Odion a powerful combo trap deck! Able to play comfortably into Maxx C, Mulcharmies, Droll, Nibiru and even Dimension Shifter, while being ultra consistent and packing 20+ staple slots... Odion's strategy has surprisingly been incredibly competent even in the hyper competitive Duelist Cup defeating the likes of Dracotail, Mitsurugi and Maliss!

Not only do you get to spam the field repeatedly with 2-3 Apophis the Swamp Deity's omni-negates, when paired with Statue of Anguish Pattern all these trap monsters become "pops!" All these cards are searchable and summonable turn 1 thanks to Odion's signature strategy, activating trap cards the same turn they were set with "Temple of the Kings," another iconic piece of Yugioh anime history now suddenly made competitive! 

Just like the "pure" Odion deck, the main strategy is to dominate your opponent with multiple negate/pops with your Apophis trap cards. However, the difference is that Fiendsmith adds a whole new layer of interactions that your opponent has to deal with, either by baiting their handtraps or facing down Desirae's omni-negate If you thought Odion was strong, how about Odion AND the strongest engine in the format?

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: now with a few more super poly targets
FIRE KING JURRAC DECK META YGO
deck_description: Playing Fire King in the current meta is not easy. The deck's start is fragile, but if we know how to dodge interruptions and master it, it can still make its mark. Since September 2025, I have tested various lists to include the Jurrac lineup without giving up the cards that help us play second (HTs). This list is a return to the origins, when Fire King was played with the Pots. Avoid Fossil Dig, it often just makes us draw Droll and reduces the deck's flex. I keep Miscellaneousaurus, but not the Bridge that sends it to the graveyard, because to resolve Meteor we often have to sacrifice other crucial combo lines. The extra deck contains only what is necessary; the side deck offers powerful answers to decks that dominate this meta. Leave a comment with suggestions.
Deck will change over time depending on testing.

This deck got extenders for days. Play through all the interruptions. We don't care about droll, we have unchained. Even under charmies you can set up several interactions while only giving them 1 draw in most cases. Summon sorceress is our replacement for moon- the standard bridge into fiendsmith combo is now:

NS Dark beckoning beast (spirit gates and throne search this) > CL1 beast to add spirit gates > activate gates CL1 to add chaos summoning beast, Extra normal chaos summoning beast with beckoning beast effect > link both into yama > cl1 yama to add aruha > activate gates other effect, discard a random card except aruha to summon beckoning beast/chaos beast from gy > link yama and your revived beast into summon sorc > summon sorc CL1 to summon aruha to opponents field and engraver to your field from your deck.

Tour guide gets you there too, but the line is different.

I didn't seem to have good luck against those decks and it seemed like my opponent always had answers to whatever I tried to do.

Your starters are: Crystron Smiger, Crystron Inclusion, Crystron Sulfefnir, Speedroid Terrortop, Foolish Burial, Foolish burial goods, and Scrap Recycler. deck_excerpt: ALL IT TAKES IS ONE BAD LADDER SESSION...
deck_description:
Playing too much 140 IQ combo decks destroy whats left of your brain cells? Did you lose too much dice rolls? Did you fall all the the way down to your base rank due to 10+ losses in a row? Seems you had a TERRIBLE ladder day! Time to STUN!

Activate Morganite cards, get cool benefits, then stun your opponent to death with the Vanity and Majesty cards! Not only that, you can use the full suite of Dominus cards to stop your opponent from playing! Your games with this unique stun deck end with either you leaving since you cannot win with your current set-up, or your opponent insta-scooping due to the stun monsters on your field. This deck is one of the quickest ways to climb up ladder! (Your opponent may hate you for using it though).

deck_name: Trader Offer: You get to draw cards, I get to play Slifer
deck_description: I've made a group hug slifer deck, like a few others have.

On the Shining Sarcophagus Engine

A small Shining Sarcophagus engine grants access to dark extenders, a rank 8 Xyz, and/or Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon.

Dark Magician Girl the Magician's Apprentice can special summon herself from your hand by discarding a card, and she searches for Shining Sarcophagus on her normal or special summon.

Shining Sarcophagus can search for Dark Magician Girl or Gandora-G the Dragon of Destruction.

Gandora-G can special summon itself from your hand if you control a Shining Sarcophagus. Its second ignition effect is great for board breaking because it can destroy, then banish as many cards on the field as possible, then special a Dark Magician Girl from your deck.

If you've activated a spell during your turn, then you can summon Dark Magician of Destruction by banishing a Dark Magician Girl you control. This spell would usually be the Shining Sarcophagus she searched for. If the Dark Magician of Destruction is special summoned, then he can search for The Gaze of Timaeus, which allows you to fusion summon Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon by shuffling a Dark Magician you control or in your graveyard back into the deck, but it's banished during the end phase of the next turn. Dark Magician of Destruction's name is changed to Dark Magician while he's face-up on the field and in the graveyard, so you can use him as Link or Xyz material with Gandora-G, then shuffle it from your graveyard back into the extra deck with The Gaze of Timaeus later. Don't worry about your Dark Dragoon getting banished because he serves to protect your core Orcust plays.

The Rank 8s

Gandora-G + Dark Magician of Destruction = A rank 8 Xyz

Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord is a quick effect monster negate.

The Zombie Vampire can mill an Orcust monster with some luck.

Xyz summoning Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star with two level 8s can grant access to Galatea-I, the Orcust Automaton if you're in a pinch.

Placement: 1st Place

I've been a long term Shinobird fan but the deck is very hard to make functional because of the awkward combination of Ritual + Spirit, both of which are not great. 

However, in Genesys format, the deck has a possibility to shine. The format is weaker, and no one is really prepared for this deck or even really understands what it does. 

The deck plays shifter to its benefit; you don't always want to activate it turn 1 in case you're going first and would rather have your ritual monsters in the grave, but it barely affects you going second and if your smaller rituals are banished after being properly summoned, they come back. 

Points are on 

3 Shifter, 3 Pre Preparation of Rites, 2 Preparation of Rites, 1 Ichiki Sayori Hime, 3 Manju the ten thousand hands

And 3 copies of Mulcharmy Fuwalos in the side

As I am running Manju and extra copies of Nikitama + Sakitama (both fairies), I managed to fit in playsets of Herald of Orange Light and Herald of Green Light. I wanted to try and fit in the shufflers too but the deck already struggles to function so it felt like a bridge too far. 

With 2 Sakitama, 2 Nikitama, 1 Ichiki, 3 Manju, 6 Heralds, we are at 14 fairies to fuel their discard effect, so it seemed like a worthwhile option. We also have numerous searchers with Manju and the Prep cards so hopefully this will allow us to access our engine reliably. 

Usually this deck is ran blind second because the two boss monsters are much better when they have targets to shuffle or bounce. In this instance I'm trying another tech option in two copies of the Vaylantz field spells, as each one sets the other to your opponents field. This allows you to have a valid target for Shinobaroness' powerful shuffle and summon from deck ability for a Turn 1 Amano Iwato that does not bounce back. 

Therefore your opponent has to have dark hole or imperm in order to use Monster Effects, or have an inherent summon that is 2000+ to out it. 

Other options to consider are using 33 points on Terraforming for easier access to either Vaylantz or Shinobirds field spell, running 3 copies of everything relevant including Amano Iwato, or prioritising Called by the Grave at 20 points. 

You could make a pure blind second version of the deck using your points on Super Poly, Droplet or more charmies. 

There are lots of options. Code Igniter is a recent rank 4 that benefits the deck by allowing you to ritual summon with only rank 4s and a ritual monster

deck_excerpt: Shamelessly stolen from Frozen Card Gaming, for my own use. Made some minor alterations for taste.
deck_description:
Link to the deck profile: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mZX-8SGuoCA&t=458s

I love unchained, but they just can't keep up in advanced. So, might as well try them in Genesys (even if I lose my beloved A-Bomb).

I had an idea for a similar list, but never figured out the details. Luckily, Frozen Card Gaming worked them out for me.

Crystron with little extra spice, and 6 points left.

Combo lines and the end board are pretty much the same as we did playing pure crystron in advanced before k9 stuff, except you can now go rosenix and revolution into ancient fairy dragon then into crystal wing to protect your combo. It's only worth to commit if your hand is rosenix + revolution + crystron starter, and the combo goes as follow:

 revolution + rosenix + Sulfador:.

Normal Summon rosenix, synchro into ancient fairy dragon with revolution in hand, revolution eff to comeback as level 1 then synchro into crystal wing, then rosenix in gy to make the token, sulfador eff destroying the token then crystron fullcombo.

the combo can vary if you open sulfefnir + any crystron instead of rosenix or a starter, like you can go sulfenir to summon rosenix if you had a good discard like thytsvern or smiger. 

If the gy eff of tristaros gets interrupted, going tidal discarding revolution to make crystal wing with eleskelutus can be a option.

fishborg harpooner is just a worse "jokul" as it adds a second 2 card combo with sulfador, or with smiger/thystvern since to get them in the gy.

Still havent confirmed on f extra deck, I was using river stormer and accel synchron before but I went 8 games in a row without ever needing either so now I'm testing formula and black rose, I have not summoned navy mech yet. Some generic level 5 synchros can be a option to replace them since, although rare, if the deck is bricking is probably because you had something like a bunch of rosenixes and harpooners in hand, then you can try to go into Kewl Tune RS just so your board is not empty, or scrap all that and put ultimate slayer targets.

deck_excerpt: The December 2025 GENESYS points update makes Branded the most powerful and consistent deck of the format!
deck_description:
Forget Kewl Tunes, Crystron and Dragon Rulers, the December 2025 GENESYS points update makes Branded the most powerful and consistent deck of the format!

The excessive points slapped on the Albaz Extra Deck fusions due to the existence of the card "The Fallen & the Virtuous," has been reverted, with most of the points being dumped on the latter. Now essential Albaz fusions like Titaniklad and Albion are cheaper or free points-wise, giving this beloved fusion strategy about 25 more points to play with! 

I've personally placed points on consistency combo pieces such as an additional Quem (3 points) and Bystial Saronir (a whopping 20 points)! I think it's justified to spend such a large amount of points on Saronir since it opens up combo routes with Granguignol/Albion the Shrouded Dragon.Quem to search out any Branded spell or trap, which usually is Branded Fusion. Consistency is king, since the strategy can already comfortably play going first of second!

Another incredible development (or lack there-of) from the December 2025 points list update is the lack of hits to the small Dracotail engine this deck uses (x1 Phryxul, x1 Urgula, x1 Pan, x3 Rahu, x1 Horn and x2 Gulamel). These cards remain free, while the only minor hit to the engine is just 3 points to Dracotail Flame, which Branded has plenty to use after the points update! Dracotail continues to allow the deck to plow through boards going second, since a single Rahu results in multiple destroyed cards, several set Dracotail spells/traps and a 2800ATK beatstick to beat over with in the battle phase.

As for me, I'm farming my GENESYS Locals with this deck, I've been mostly undefeated so far with my results! You can do it too! :D

Here is the main combo for GENESYS Branded featuring 1 Aluber, 1 monster and 2 discards: 

1. Normal summon Aluber and activate Aluber's effect to search Branded Fusion. 

2. Activate Branded Fusion to summon Albion, using Albaz and Phryxul from deck. 

3. CL1 Albion to fusion summon Lubellion using Albaz + Aluber, CL2 Phryxul to set from deck Rahu Dracotail. 

4. Activate Lubellion discarding 1 card fusion summon Mirrorjade using Lubellion + Albaz. 

5. Activate Rahu Dracotail to fusion summon Gulamel, using any monster in hand and Dracotail Pan from deck. 

6. Activate Pan's effect to set any Dracotail trap from deck (whatever is relevant to the matchup) and to destroy Albion on field. 

7. During the End Phase, Albion adds to hand Branded Opening. 

8. Activate Branded Opening to summon from deck Quem. 

9. Activate Quem to send to GY Cartesia. 

During your opponent's turn, Quem can summon Cartesia for further fusion plays, Mirrorjade can banish a monster and Dracotail trap with Gulamel's targeted destruction! This is the simplest combo, but stronger endboards can be made if you have the correct hand. 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_name: A-to-Z, But I Know How the Cards Work Unlike Everyone Else
deck_excerpt: Because we all just like combining all our robots together.
deck_description:
This is a A-to-Z Deck that has a way to bring out A-to-Z while featuring other tools to help make for a fun experience. A lot of the decks that have A-to-Z either don't have a way to bring it out or just are pretty bad. This won't be the most meta deck, but it should be a fun way to get out beloved creatures. The side deck can allow you to focus more on ABC or the XYZ Hyper Dragon Cannon by swapping out the original pieces which are all Garnets. This is based on a deck I used in Master Duel, but I tried to modify it for the TCG. I have recently gotten back into paper, so I hope to get this tested more. Always open for feedback.

The main through line for this deck is to get X-Hyper Cannon out. Ideally its in your opening hand or you use Union Activation to throw X-Head Cannon into the GY and get it. You will search and attack B-Buster Drake and then special summon it. From there, link into Platinum Gadget and search for Y-Yare Head. Special summon it and then attach B-Buster Drake from the GY and special summon it again. Then Fusion Summon Union Controller by banishing Platinum Gadget and Y-Yare Head. Search for Union Hanger, play it, and then search for Z-Zillion Tank. When you summon Z-Zillion Tank, you will attach the banished Y-Yare Head and let the Union Hanger Trigger activate to add Union Driver. Then use Union Driver to switch to B-Buster Drake or one of the other ABCs. You will special summon it and Y-Yare Head and Y-Yare Head target B-Buster Drake (There will be a lot of it).

Using B-Buster Drake and A-Assualt Core, you will want to Link Summon Sillohoute Rabbit and set the continuous trap. Add any ABC or original XYZ monster(s) to your hand or graveyard. You can use two B-Buster Drakes as well, it is important to make sure to have two Light Monsters in your hand so manage your robots accordingly.

Use Y-Yare Head and Z-Zillion Tank to go into Galaxy Photon Dragon, it is important to use these two as if you use the other ABCs, they will not trigger their GY effects. Galaxy Photo Dragon will detach either monster to bring in Galaxy Soldier to your hand. You will discard a Light ABC or XYZ to bring out Galaxy Soldier and then use it's effect to bring in another. Xyz summon Cyber Dragon Nova and then Xyz Cyber Dragon Infinity. 

Once there you can go a few different paths, if you have managed your XYZ materials accordingly, you should be able to bring out XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon while you only have two other monsters in the main monster zones. You will then use its effect to reveal the OG XYZ-Dragon Cannon and banish XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon to bring out the three pieces from the GY. Then banish the three OG to bring out XYZ-Dragon Cannon.

From there, you can banish ABC pieces to bring out ABC-Dragon Buster. Then if both are on the field, you can bring out A-to-Z Dragon Buster Cannon. 

If you get Terraforming, it can help you bring out Union Hanger or more optiminally Therion Discolosseum to bring out Therion "King" Regulus. Equip him with a ABC based on what you need.

That is the main combo line. Depending on your opening hand and starter creatures, you can be a little flexible based on what you use. The Utopia Cards where added for an alternate monster if you get stalled in the combo or trying to bring it around with less than optimal cards. There might be better options, as I test it I will find out.

deck_excerpt: Merry Christmas from Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon
deck_description: Earlier yesterday, I published episode 92 of Yu-Gi-Oh! deck_excerpt: Maliceverous + Diabellstar + idk whatever I could fit into this fiend based engine
deck_description: I kinda just got these in masterduel, the maliceverous cards, and ever since I've been compelled to make somethign with them. Idk why idek how.

Medius the Pure is actually a solid rank 4 engine all by himself. With the help of Artmage academic arts acropolis's extra normal summon, Medius's ability and Artmage vandalism assault you get easy access to a rank 4 XYZ in addition to the rest of the artmage endboard. Azamina is mostly there to play around nibiru the primal being. 


 

by using Medius's second ability+The extra normal of artmage academic arts acropolis you can make a rank 4 at significant cost. 

There are 2 major good options for rank 4 

The first is Giant hand/ Tornado dragon and other generic rank 4s, they can just do the job in a pinch

The second path involves playing bricks

The first brick build is Utopia Double or nothing + Ultimate Leo utopia ray, which adds 2 bricks BUT lets you have 2 monster negates in your endboard

The second one is cooler, and it's Raiders Knight into Raidraptor  Brave Strix finding Raidraptor Glorious bright. This gives you a Solemn, which is extra nice because it gives your endboard layering which you so desperately want.  Specifically it lets you have a spell/trap negate *that isn't a monster effect* in play.  with 2 omni negates  1 monster negate and a monster pop in your GY you're in a pretty scary position overall for many decks. 

in order to facilitate this instead of playing the classic 3 Fusion deployment 1 Cartesia, we instead play 3 Summoner monk and 1 more board breaker.

The current theory is I'll either open medius or the field spell, if you open both you end up with a 4 negate endboard. though it kinda depends on how much you want to play around nibiru how much followup you have, the less you play around nibiru the stronger your endboard becomes. 

The ability to go from "nib proof by weaker" to "oh my god wtf" is actually really nice.  you have the ability to make a 4 negate endboard which I say "good luck :smile:

One other option to consider in the extra deck is Guardian chimera,  it allows for extra ceiling when going first and is an interesting multipop going second, especially combined w/ty-phon but ehh it's 33 points :/

24 engine 16 non-engine but have strong ceiling anyway due to being able to convert non-engine to engine cheaply

Yugi Muto uses a Silent/Toy Deck focusing on cards that activate their effects over time like his "Silent Magician" and "Silent Swordsman", symbolizing the growth that Yugi has undergone on his journey. The Deck notably omits the "Dark Magician" and its related cards, representing the strength that Yugi has without the help of Yami Yugi, and proving that he is ready to live without him.

Utilizing defensive and stalling tactics through cards like "Marshmallon" and "Swords of Revealing Light", Yugi supports his Silent Monsters so that they can level-up and increase their strength. He also uses multiple Trap Cards that interrupt the opponent's Battle Phase, such as "Negate Attack", "Thunder of Ruler" and "Miracle Locus", replacing the anime-only "Soul Shield", "Mirage Ruler" and "Ambush Shield". Another powerful Trap Card that Yugi uses, and activates its effect over time is "Shattered Axe", replacing the anime-only "Ground Erosion". Finally, "Monster Reincarnation" allows the Silent Monsters and Gandora to be recovered from the Graveyard. A notable additions to the Deck is "Dark Bribe", which is meant to help "Silent Magician LV4" level-up faster.

The Deck also makes use of several Toy and Gadget Cards, showing Yugi's playful side and love for games. "Blockman" is yet another Monster that activates its effect over time, while the Gadgets are supported by cards like "Ties of the Brethren" and the newly added "Double Summon". These can also be used to swarm the field with Monsters and boost the effect of "Gandora the Dragon of Destruction", which Yugi uses as a last resort, to banish all Cards on the field and aim for a direct attack.

Almost every one of Yugi's Monsters can be searched from the Deck using "Witch of the Black Forest", "Sangan", "Soul Rope", the newly added "Setuppercut", and of course "Gold Sarcophagus", which again activates over time. The only missing Card is the anime-only "Turn Jump", which supports every aspect of this Deck.

Yami Marik runs an Immortality-Torture Deck focusing on torturing the opponent and slowly burning his life points, while stalling the game long enough to draw and summon his Egyptian God Card and finish the duel.

His cards slowly drain his opponent's strength, such as discarding cards from their hand with "Helpoemer", and burning them with "Coffin Seller", "Nightmare Wheel", "Drillago", and his ultimate torture machine: "Lava Golem". To stall the game, Yami Marik uses indestructible Monsters such as his "Egyptian God Slime"and three copies of "Viser Des", replacing the anime-only "Plasma Eel", and some of the cards previously used by Rare Hunters such as "Mask of Restrict" and "Nightmare's Steelcage". Notable additions to the deck are "Doomdog Octhros" which allows him to search for his "Lava Golem"; "Mystic Tomato" which allows him to search and summon his "Legendary Fiend"; and "Barrel Behind the Door" which synergizes well with his "Granadora".

With "The WInged Dragon of Ra" as his trump card, his entire deck focuses on summoning "Ra", preferably after the opponent has been burnt for 4000+ damage, and finishing the duel. Yami Marik uses a variety of cards to discard it to the Graveyard, e.g. "Foolish Burial" or "Rope of Life", and then revive it with "Monster Reborn". If "Monster Reborn" is not in his hand, he searches for it with "Left Arm Offering". He further relies on retrieving "Monster Reborn" to his hand after using it initially to continue to revive "Ra" again and again, using "Magical Stone Excavation" and "Spell Reclamation", which comes to replace the anime-only "Zombie's Jewel". Since "Ra" cannot be Special Summoned, three copies of "Dark Spell Regeneration" are run, that would allow for "Ra" to be brought back from the Graveyard using "Monster Reborn". Finally, "Blaze Cannon" and "Sun God Unification" are added to give "Ra" some of its anime effects and to allow Yami Marik to restore his Life Points before "Ra" leaves the field.

deck_excerpt: On the 6th day of GXmas, Yubel gave to me... this weird arm thingy? - GX Anime Series #72
deck_description:
GX Character Series deck #72 (Season 3)

Marcel Bonaparte - Exodia deck

 

 

Note: This character series is made for fun/casual playability and balance, not strict anime accuracy (impossible with most characters). Card pool was limited (almost entirely) to GX era for authenticity and some post-release cards from the anime.

Strengths:
A tricky deck and lesser known archetype that makes for a great sleeper deck. Overall great protections against destruction from either battle or card effects. No battle damage taken during battles. Use the opponent's ATK power against themselves. Lots of searching ability. Graveyard revivals and graveyard effects. Can easily 'snatch steal' opponent's monsters. Can easily wipe monster zones with kaijus and lava golem, removing those pesky negate cards. Pretty consistent and versatile with a handful of options and a modicum of control. 

 

Goal:
Go second, wipe their board and tribute their strong effect monsters (especially negates) with your Kaijus or Lava Golem. Equip Double Edged Sword to your kaiju/golem or their strongest available ATK on the field, hit them multiple times in one turn (using Heavenly Gate field spell, or Uzuhime's ability) for massive reflect damage and OTK. 

**NOTE: Due to Mikanko monsters' effects, the battle damage that you would normally take from attacking the opponent with a Double Edged Sword on their monster, is 'ALSO' reflected back to the opponent - essentially the damage they take is doubled. A single attack on a monster with 4000 or higher ATK wins the game, and 2000 of that atk power comes from the equip itself, so a 2k atk power monster left on the field can spell instant doom for the opponent**


Main combo: (TBA)


Secondary combos:

Make use of Fire Dance with/and/or Sanaki to get multiple mikankos on the field in one turn. You can use Ha-Re's ability to search for Fire Dance. 

Mikanko Rivalry trap can activate either Angelica's Ring (spell negate) or Axe of Fools (monster eff negate) during your opponent's turn. 

Equip Water Arabesque to your kaijus/golem on the opponent's field to return them to your hand (usually after attacking them for battle damage, in MP2), get a free summon, and then be able to use their special summon tribute effects again in the same or next turn. Recycling kaijus is broken as hell, and i love it. >=)

 

 

Weaknesses:

Going first!

Lack of monsters on opponent's field / empty field.

Yosenjus and Spirit arcehtypes.

Backrow removal.

Monster effect negation.

Return to deck (drowning mirror force etc.)

Certain floodgates - magic jamming, special summon blocking, type or attribute restirction etc. 


Note - 

Depending on your format, swap out the Maxx-Cs and use the suggestions in the side deck to tweak it to your liking and play style.

deck_excerpt: New fusions awaken! Come forth, Artmages!
deck_description: This deck can run Dragon's Mind to negate monster, spell, and trap effects that activate on the field, then destroy them. Artmage Diactorus meets the requirements for Dragon's Mind, and a board of Diactorus + Dragon's Mind provides up to 2 of these omni-negates in a turn. Artmage Litera can easily revive Diactorus if he's sent to your graveyard, making this combo hard to deal with. Lastly, by paying 2500 life points, Dragon's Mind can set itself from your graveyard to your field, which makes it great for grind games and discard fodder for Artmage Academic Arcane Arts Acropolis.
