deck_excerpt: Very synergistic engines with heavy bridging.
deck_description: Fun deck, lots of interesting combo lines and bridging. Your first goal is to do stupid broken stuff with Psychics, ideally ending on Psychic Blaster Mk-II / one of the Level 11 Synchros, and a Teleport Fusion. Your second goal is to do stupid broken stuff with Kashtiras, locking your opponent's field with Shangri-Ira, setting up a Fenrir and Unicorn, sitting on Ariseheart's big fat Macro, etc. In an ideal world, you're bridging between the two of these with cards like Parallel Teleport, to get the both of best endboards or, at the very least, a toolbox summon of any specific maindeck Kashtira during your opponent's turn. You also have a lot of flexibility to go into other lines, with Prototype Psychic Blaster letting you get Psychic Blaster Mk-II out without using your Silent Psychic Magician for the turn, the Kashtiras letting you easily go into Baronne or Chengying, etc. There's significant room to improve this specific list, though.

deck_excerpt: dark magician of chaos, dark magician
deck_description: Simple Deck focused on attack that I enjoy playing with friends

Deck focused on going second and otking. With the loss of Droll this decks in a fantastic spot to go second and blowout an opponent, crack their board and swing for game. You have access to multiple 1 card combos with even more 2 card combos that can outright kill an opponents board and them. In addition the lack of core point values means all points are put into the good going second hand traps, and on the flip side means the deck can be modified to go first with different point allotments.

With the final points reduction putting all ninja cards at 0 theres finally room to invest it all into non engine, plenty of room to play books for more flip control or handtraps for a easier transition from standard format to genesys. The ability to play the best blowout card in the side like evenly or even main Nibiru is going first deck puts the pressure on the opponent to either play into the hand traps or play conservatively which this deck excels at.

The recent points update sadly took our best 1 card starter in Dodododo warrior from the deck, and the major points on regulus and mathmech means to keep playing the deck youre going to have to cut down on nonengine. However the lack of droll means almost all of your plays will go through without much worry, and even a half board into a mulcharmmy is 2-3 interuptions on its own. You will struggle playing into an established board now, but the sharks and mathmechs should help before you slap down a Zeus that can win matches on its own.

This Burn deck it's a combination of Fire Speed Burn & Tax Burn decks.

The main goal is to be a pain in the...you know what, by using continuity cards like Curse of Darkness or Chain Energy as in Tax Burn, and inflicting damage as well with cards like Meteor of Destruction and Tremendous Fire from Speed Burn.

I often found out that Tax Burn is a slow-play deck, but with some test hands I recently found out that this would be a good combination of cards even with a "bad start".
Remember to always try to lock with Curse and Chain to an extra fast win ^^.

The Side is purely subjective, but this one I made is for a generic interaction with the common decks if you need a boost on attack, as well with Secret Barrel & Ojama Trio to switch into a classic Burn deck.

HAVE FUN!

deck_excerpt: it doesn't matter what your name is!  it doesn't matter- matter- matter- matter-
deck_description:
use this hybrid deck to take opponents by surprise!  

there is an earlier version of this deck which I based this deck's idea off of- in that, nightmare throne is used as a garnet to search kepler and normal summon it from hand.  I felt the new DDD support makes nightmare throne irrelevant, since dc zero king summons kepler to the field, which then activates kepler to get your first search off (dc zero king cannot be drolled unlike nightmare throne), while keeping your normal summon. there is an upside to nightmare throne without machinex + dc zero king - it doesnt lock you, can be used to bait ash if you got kepler already, but nightmare throne being ashed or drolled when you need it is worse than getting your kepler ashed or drolled.

optimal opener is 1 gate / machinex, 1 fiendsmith monster (if not, its okay, we can make moon first).   

first goal is to make desirae equipped with sequence, then scale machinex, activate effect, place dc zero king (zk) on the field, zk effect pop machinex, then (evaluating hand), either [A.] summon kepler (searching dc gate, to get scale surveyor or gryphon into hand -- or dc swamp king if you already drew 1 of them),  or [B.] summon copernicus (sending lance soldier, activate lance soldier to pop dc zk to synchro into clevis, special back lance)  in order to link gilgamesh and get into your DDDs comboing under desirae's quick effect target-negate protection. 

Summary:  This deck is structured to summon your fiendsmiths first before committing to pivoting to DDD's, and includes newer DDDs for fans of this deck.

strategy:  this deck does not expect to particularly keep its contracts until the next turn (using deviser's effects to stop the opponent from making board presence with monsters)

I like putting scale surveyor and copernicus into scale zone if I did not summon copernicus yet.  I also put gryphon and scale surveyor in too. 

so if you can't make moon or requiem, then just pivot.  an end-board looks like: zeus ragnarock, deviser king machinex, high king caesar, cursed king siegfried, +/- desirae with sequence equipped, +/- set ddd headhunt. 

you can't activate Machinex's effect in scale zone if placed there by Gilgamesh, it must be placed there by you - just thought that would be an important note.

send any thoughts or points, the handtraps could be replaced.  side deck is customizable, I just included some cards you may want to consider, and others I like.

deck_excerpt: Time to trade out our handtraps for power spells! Fellow Aces! Let us now activate our Sky Striker Special Maneuver - BOARD BREAK!!!
deck_description:
With the rise of Dracotail and the fall of Maliss, fields have become a lot more fragile and crackable... Time to trade out our handtraps for power spells! Fellow Aces! Let us now activate our Sky Striker Special Maneuver - BOARD BREAK!!! 

With Sky Striker at full power with all it's support and tools at it's disposal in Masterduel, the Raye remains as competitive as ever, fighting toe-to-toe with ladder heavyweights like Mitsurugi, Dracotail, Branded, Maliss and Ryzeal! The strategy can comfortably play through turn ending handtraps like Maxx C, Mulcharmies, Nibiru and even Droll (with certain hands)! Don't believe me? Sky Striker even reached top 8 in points in December 2025's Duelist Cup!

With the recent release of Masterduel Selection Pack "Future Begins Zero," Sky Striker has finally received obtained two of its most powerful cards for its arsenal! Raye is now at full power in Masterduel, and it's her turn to reign supreme!

Sky Striker Ace Zero searches any Sky Striker spell from deck, and can non-target destroy any ard on the field! While it's effects may be simple, it adds incredible consistency to Sky Striker since it directly searches Engage, the ace card of the strategy. The non-target pop also enables Sky Striker to reliably go first, finally giving the Extra Deck toolbox a form of interruption that is reliable. 

Special Maneuver Lemnisgate non-target returns to hand cards on the field whlie simultaneously recycling your Sky Striker monsters and spells from the GY, further enabling Raye's infinite grindgame! Lemnisgate can also banish iself from the GY to give you another link summon of a Sky Striker monster on the field, allowing you another layer of interruption! Finally, Lemnisgate can activate even if your main monster zones are occupied which makes it very versatile and allows the Sky Striker player to play even in sticky situations like when Raye is kaiju'd or your monster zones are clogged.

This incredible power the new support offers and the favourable conditions of the meta only leave it to the individual pilot's skill playing Sky Striker. Can you strike from the skies with the full power of an ace? 

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Mokey Mokey in defense Modey Modey
Centur-ion and Ashened have a suprising ammount of synergy. Here is a cook using the fact the best Centur-ion starter is a Dark Pyro.
deck_description:
This is a deck I have build to try and make Ashened work. originally I played with Volcanic, but I found that the ceiling was just to low and was looking at Pyro's that could be searched with Infernal Flame Banshee and found Trudea. 

The lines are highly varried as if you find one starter or the other the lines completely change. The locks of the Ashened cards can make it so you can't synchro as there are no Pyro Synchro monsters that have any value yet, but you can still use the Centur-Ion cards to set up a Synchro summon on your opponents turn.

You can if you wish to focus more on the Centur-ion part, remove the super poly's to instead play Auxila and have more points for possible hand traps. Since I found you sometimes get locked out of the Centur-ion synchro's I found it wasn't worth the 33 points to play. If it ever gets cheaper that will definitely be worth it. I am also not sure on the centur-ion spell/traps to play, currently I play 1 of each except the token generator but you can swap these around for sure.

Finally the extra deck can probably be improved, if you do not wish to focus on super poly and instead go more Centur-ion focus, you can absolutely play more synchro monsters for the Centur-ion tool box.

Pyros!

deck_excerpt: Go 2nd and swing big with big boy Exodia
deck_description:
Your starters in this deck are Shield of the Millennium Dynasty, Heart of the Blue-Eyes, Wedju Temple/Golem that Guards the Millennium Treasures and any 1 other monster, and of course, Millennium Ankh. 

Go 2nd and interrupt your opponent with a heft amount of cheap non-engine, and then swing big for your life points with The Unstoppable Exodia Incarnate!

If it's not quite enough, set Exxod Fires of Rage from your deck at the end of your turn to add a board wipe to your end board, alongside your spell/trap negate with Exodia. Then if he's still standing at the end of your opponent's turn, use his effect to set Obliterate!!! Blaze from your deck, to use next turn to wipe your opponent out.

Other than Exodia, the extra deck is full of tech options, such as Snake-Eyes Doomed Dragon whihc can be summoned using 2 monsters in the spell/trap zone (which can be Millennium monsters or monsters placed there by Wedju Temple). Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand can negate its own effects to protect it from being shuffled back by Ankh, and Garunix Eternity, Hyang of the Fire Kings is another board wipe. the Garuras, Malongs, and Aggregators are targets for Ultimate Slayer, so you can get a little more bang for your buck with it.

The side deck is 6 spots of more Shifters, some spell/trap removal if Exodia's negate isn't quite enough, some additional Exodia support, and 3 copies of The Dark - Hex-Sealed Fusion. This can be normal summoned (you don't really use your NS in this deck) and then contact fused with any of your effect monsters to make Millennium-Eyes Restrict. It's a good going first card that won't be shuffled back to your deck on actovation of Ankh, as it is a "Millennium" monster!

All in all, I enjoyed this deck when it first came out in the TCG, so it's nice to see that it could be somewhat viable in Genesys!

Enjoy!

My old Burn Turbo deck has been updated with a few new tools! It now features a usable Extra Deck that covers niche scenarios where burn is no longer a win condition. Goblin Thief was swapped out for Final Flame, trading survivability for more consistent burn damage. If the duel lasts more than 3 turns, then you're in danger anyway. Lastly, Contract with Don Thousand forces both players to lose 1000 life points on activation. This effect can't be negated by cards that prevent effect damage because it doesn't deal damage.
